1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

2
00:00:11,000 --> 00:00:17,000
Okay, this is Roan Cullen for about 20 seconds.

3
00:00:26,000 --> 00:00:34,000
Today is Friday, July 15, 2011. My name is Joe Manier of the Southern Oil History Program.

4
00:00:35,000 --> 00:00:40,000
I'm a professor at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Bill. I'm a videographer, John Bishop,

5
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:47,000
a conducted interview for the Civil Rights History Project, which is a joint undertaking of the Library of Congress.

6
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:51,000
And the Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture,

7
00:00:51,000 --> 00:00:54,000
which delighted to be in Philadelphia today with Dr. John Churchill.

8
00:00:54,000 --> 00:00:58,000
Thank you, Dr. Churchill, for inviting us to come by and spend some time with you. It's an honor of privilege.

9
00:00:58,000 --> 00:00:59,000
Thank you.

10
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:01,000
Well, you're more than welcome.

11
00:01:02,000 --> 00:01:06,000
I thought I'd start today just talking a little bit about Dr. Charles,

12
00:01:06,000 --> 00:01:08,000
and coming up and building up it.

13
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:09,000
Okay.

14
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:14,000
All right, where should I start? I was born at a very early age.

15
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:17,000
I think that's a good way to begin.

16
00:01:21,000 --> 00:01:27,000
I guess I can think of a couple of incidents that were life-changing.

17
00:01:28,000 --> 00:01:30,000
I'll talk about those.

18
00:01:30,000 --> 00:01:39,000
When I was in about the first of all, I was born with a very extreme case of myopia.

19
00:01:39,000 --> 00:01:48,000
So I went to a site saving school back in those days. They had a site saving program.

20
00:01:49,000 --> 00:02:02,000
And when I was in about the fifth grade, I experienced my first set of circumstances where I face discrimination.

21
00:02:04,000 --> 00:02:09,000
And it's interesting because I wasn't discriminated against because I was black, but because I was a site saver.

22
00:02:10,000 --> 00:02:14,000
In that school, we had...

23
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:21,000
It was in a regular school. In fact, it was in T.M. Peer School, which is a school in North Philadelphia.

24
00:02:21,000 --> 00:02:26,000
I believe it's at 23rd and Canberra, if I remember it correctly.

25
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:33,000
And at that school, which was a, quote, regular school, they had a site-saving program.

26
00:02:34,000 --> 00:02:38,000
And of course, what site-saving was is that we had larger print...

27
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:42,000
You know, we would print larger, bigger lines.

28
00:02:42,000 --> 00:02:46,000
And we had a safety patrol.

29
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:52,000
But there was segregation in the school. The regular students were where they were.

30
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:56,000
The site-savvers had their own lunchroom. Site-savvers had their own safety patrol.

31
00:02:56,000 --> 00:02:59,000
I was on that safety patrol.

32
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:13,000
The problems of the segregation, if you will, and discrimination was that a regular safety could tell any student,

33
00:03:13,000 --> 00:03:19,000
site-saver or regular to do whatever they needed to do, but site-saving safety.

34
00:03:19,000 --> 00:03:23,000
And I was one of those could only talk to site-saver.

35
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:29,000
So when I was in the fifth grade, I got very upset about it, talked to one of my teachers.

36
00:03:29,000 --> 00:03:36,000
And she suggested that I run for student council and raise the issue there.

37
00:03:36,000 --> 00:03:42,000
So an interesting thing occurred. I did run for student council, got on to student council.

38
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:52,000
And in fact, kind of ended up being president of student council, and forgot completely about the issue that sent me there.

39
00:03:53,000 --> 00:04:04,000
So I took that as a learning experience as I reflect back, that the error that I made in fifth grade was to think that,

40
00:04:04,000 --> 00:04:09,000
to forget my identity. And my identity at that point was a site-saver.

41
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:14,000
And my role was to make sure that I fought for the best interests of site-savvers.

42
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:24,000
Well, I got caught up in the fun of being accepted by the regulars as the school president and lost that focus.

43
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:35,000
And so that lesson, which of course I didn't learn in fifth grade, but I certainly learned today afterwards, helped me to focus as an older person.

44
00:04:35,000 --> 00:04:41,000
By the time I got to high school, I figured out where I had screwed up.

45
00:04:42,000 --> 00:04:53,000
Another event, when I was in seventh grade, that could have changed my life forever, was being bullied.

46
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:58,000
And people talk about bullying today. Gee, whiz was I bullied. There was a sky.

47
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:01,000
I won't mention his name. He may he rest in peace.

48
00:05:02,000 --> 00:05:13,000
But he used to beat me up every day. And my first way of handling it was to try to run away from him.

49
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:19,000
Every time I tried to get away from him, he would beat me and make it worse because I avoided him.

50
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:26,000
The next thing I tried was to fight him back. That was futile.

51
00:05:26,000 --> 00:05:32,000
He was bigger, better, and better than me. And so he would beat me worse.

52
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:43,000
In deep frustration, I talked to some of my student friends of mine and I said, hey, I talked to my friend and said, look, what am I going to do?

53
00:05:43,000 --> 00:05:54,000
He, my friend, referred me to a young man who was a Ukrainian descent, who told me that he take care of it.

54
00:05:54,000 --> 00:06:00,000
Now, I got to tell you about this guy. I'm not going to mention his name, but I got to tell you about my Ukrainian friend.

55
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:09,000
He was a Nazi. He could just about quote verbatim, mine comp.

56
00:06:10,000 --> 00:06:18,000
He loved the ground-hittler walk-doney, talked about him all the time. But there were some weird things about this young man.

57
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:19,000
It's nice to hear that.

58
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:27,000
This is in, yeah, the weird thing about him is one, he wasn't blonde, he wasn't blue-eyed, he was brown-hired, and brown-eyed.

59
00:06:27,000 --> 00:06:30,000
And he wasn't a German, and he was a Ukrainian.

60
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:39,000
The second thing is his favorite teacher was Jewish, and not the German teacher we had on staff who was a rabid showmanist.

61
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:50,000
And to show you how she felt about the black students in her class, she told us all we had to do was fly airplanes while she taught the white kids on the other side of the moon.

62
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:52,000
And Russell couldn't stand her.

63
00:06:53,000 --> 00:07:02,000
His best friend, oh I shouldn't mention his name, but it's okay. His best friend was not a German, but an African-American.

64
00:07:02,000 --> 00:07:07,000
And of course, he didn't come to the United States because he benefited from Nazism.

65
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:12,000
So I kind of anomalous his whole interest in it.

66
00:07:12,000 --> 00:07:19,000
But anyway, what he did was he told me he helped me out. So the next day he brought me a zip gun.

67
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:25,000
And he brought me some 22 caliber bullets, and he made the gun for me for free and gave me the bullets for free.

68
00:07:25,000 --> 00:07:32,000
And that day I went home and determined how I would end the life of my torturer.

69
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:43,000
Without so much thinking about it, I mean I put the gun in my pocket, went to school the next day, and this day I looked for my tormentor.

70
00:07:43,000 --> 00:07:51,000
And I found him in the school yard and asked him, why are you always messing with me? Why are you trying to make my life miserable?

71
00:07:51,000 --> 00:08:03,000
And he knew that I was too bold for my recent behavior. So he said, oh you must have a gun. You must think you're going to hurt me.

72
00:08:03,000 --> 00:08:14,000
And I was going to pull the gun out, and at that very moment, as he was coming toward me, I for the first time thought, if I do this, I'm going to jail.

73
00:08:14,000 --> 00:08:20,000
And the worst thing that can happen, worst in jail is I would disappoint my mother.

74
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:32,000
And so I didn't pull it. He beat me that day. But he beat me. I've described it as the way he beat me was like a person who does their due diligence.

75
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:42,000
It's like, because you did this, I have to, to save face, I have to do something to you. But it was not at the level that he usually would beat me.

76
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:50,000
It was sort of like a show. He beat me. It wasn't hard. It didn't hurt. And he walked away. And he never bothered me again.

77
00:08:50,000 --> 00:09:03,000
But six months later, he was dead. He was a member of a gang, and he got killed. So what I learned from that was that I could have taken an action that would have ruined the rest of my life.

78
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:11,000
And until the moment it hit me, I didn't even consider all those things that I considered on the day that it happened.

79
00:09:11,000 --> 00:09:29,000
I would say that those two childhood memories, aside from the fact that those were the memories that really shaped the way I think shaped, helped shape the way I deal with problems, looking for solutions other than killing people.

80
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:35,000
And the other person who was really strong in my life was of course my mother, who...

81
00:09:35,000 --> 00:09:36,000
Sure.

82
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:41,000
...who just went to follow up on that one question before you talk about your mom. Was that really white or black?

83
00:09:41,000 --> 00:09:44,000
He was black.

84
00:09:44,000 --> 00:09:59,000
So, and of course in those days, the only notion I had about race in that time was the way my third grade teacher talked to me.

85
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:14,000
Because one day, and by the way, the guy who gave me the gun, we had gone to school. We stayed in sight saving from second grade through eighth grade before people go to junior high school.

86
00:10:14,000 --> 00:10:26,000
But in third grade, this German teacher said, looked at me and said, how's your mommy?

87
00:10:26,000 --> 00:10:44,000
And I felt funny about it. So when I went home and told my mother that the teacher said, how's my mommy? And it was something about the sound and the tone that wasn't cool that my mother said, when you go back to school tomorrow and ask her how's her mommy?

88
00:10:44,000 --> 00:10:56,000
But I knew there was something up, but it was a mixed group of kids. I mean we had black and white students. So I didn't have a sense except for that teacher and the other thing.

89
00:10:56,000 --> 00:11:05,000
There's something else that we had to deal with in school when I was going to school, was our teachers and counselors, except for the...

90
00:11:05,000 --> 00:11:19,000
I had two teachers that I remember. Mrs. Maines and Mrs. Corn. These were teachers who were very supportive, always encouraging us to go do whatever we needed to do.

91
00:11:19,000 --> 00:11:29,000
But there were counselors and other people who would constantly tell us, you need to go to trade school.

92
00:11:29,000 --> 00:11:37,000
You need to go to, you know, don't try to go to college. You'll never be able to get anything. You'll never be able to go anywhere.

93
00:11:37,000 --> 00:11:47,000
And it was one guy, when I was in the ninth grade, I remember him very specifically. One teacher, our social studies teacher, and I give him credit.

94
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:59,000
He had his ideas about, you know, don't even think about it. I mean, we just tell the straight up. Don't even think about, you know, go to college if you want to, but don't think about getting the job or being able to do anything.

95
00:11:59,000 --> 00:12:05,000
What I will teach you, he didn't teach us social studies, but what he taught us was, and I give him credit to this day.

96
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:20,000
He made us get newspapers, and he taught us about the stock market. He said, you know, take practice, buy some stocks, you know, this is all theoretical.

97
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:32,000
And he would make us follow those stocks every single day, so that when we got out of his class, even though we knew no social studies, we knew how to invest in stocks.

98
00:12:32,000 --> 00:12:47,000
So I give him credit for, at least giving us a skill that we could, and he was very clear about, you know, the way money is made in the United States is nobody gets rich from working a nine to five job.

99
00:12:47,000 --> 00:12:58,000
So the way you're going to be able to do well is to get into the stock market, start small, and just keep doing it as a side thing. Keep doing it, keep doing it, and you'll end up.

100
00:12:58,000 --> 00:13:07,000
If you believe what other people tell you, and you go after a job, and think you're going to work for 25 years, and you'll live on whatever they give you, the watch, and whatever.

101
00:13:07,000 --> 00:13:22,000
And I give him credit for instilling in us. He gave us more social studies than the curriculum called for, but, but I really appreciate that. That was a lesson that was really helpful.

102
00:13:22,000 --> 00:13:33,000
I was going to go in and talk about the other major influence of all my life, which came up in that moment when I decided I better not use this gun.

103
00:13:33,000 --> 00:13:45,000
I absolutely loved my mother, and I know every kid loves his mother. But because we were, we developed a friendship.

104
00:13:45,000 --> 00:14:00,000
She was, she only had gone to high school, but she was well-read, she was, she loved music, she was a musician, and we could get into these deep conversations about different things.

105
00:14:00,000 --> 00:14:20,000
And she was very open, she was very, she looked like a traditional person, but her mind was non-traditional. She was open to new ideas, she was open to, she never made excuses for injustice wherever they were.

106
00:14:20,000 --> 00:14:36,000
She was just, you know, she was a person who, you know, read readers' digest, you know, read, you know, did this kind of stuff. And so she, she, she was a tremendous positive influence in my life.

107
00:14:36,000 --> 00:14:50,000
And she always, one of the things that she taught me so well was always examine your motives. Whenever you think about doing anything, think about why you're doing, you need to know why you're doing whatever it is you're doing.

108
00:14:50,000 --> 00:14:59,000
It may look like it's good to somebody else, but you need to know what your motives are, and examine those motives and make sure that they're in line with what's right.

109
00:14:59,000 --> 00:15:04,000
So, so she was, she was my best friend.

110
00:15:04,000 --> 00:15:08,000
So, I'll try to just one second.

111
00:15:08,000 --> 00:15:11,000
Okay.

112
00:15:11,000 --> 00:15:13,000
Okay, we'll back on after short break.

113
00:15:13,000 --> 00:15:19,000
Our church will, you mentioned about other musicians, and I know that music would be very important to you as well.

114
00:15:19,000 --> 00:15:24,000
Can you talk a little bit about her music and how you came to...

115
00:15:24,000 --> 00:15:41,000
Okay. Yeah. She was, she went to temple to take music courses because she was, she was a singer, and she had an opportunity as a singer.

116
00:15:41,000 --> 00:15:53,000
I don't know who the, the, the impassario was, but there was somebody who heard about her and offered her an opportunity to do whatever operatic.

117
00:15:53,000 --> 00:16:03,000
People do, and she turned it down on the, on the basis that she wanted to raise her children, and she wanted to, you know, just do that.

118
00:16:03,000 --> 00:16:12,000
But in the meantime, she had a choir called the Village Concert Choir, and we lived in the heart of North Philadelphia.

119
00:16:13,000 --> 00:16:29,000
And on summer nights, you could hear this choir of maybe 10 to 15 people singing Bach or Mozart or some other thing, Negro Spirituals as well.

120
00:16:29,000 --> 00:16:37,000
It was a fully rounded thing, and so there was a, there was a sense in which she, she brought, if you will, culture to the neighborhood.

121
00:16:37,000 --> 00:16:44,000
And people would just come outside and just listen as, you know, as the group was rehearsing and singing.

122
00:16:44,000 --> 00:17:03,000
She also had, you know, did individual voice lessons, piano lessons and voice lessons, and I kind of learned, there was a time when she got ill, and there were students coming, and I kind of figured out how I could fake, well, fake during the teaching.

123
00:17:03,000 --> 00:17:32,000
And it was easy because I was around a lot, and I would hear, you know, Saturday after Saturday, people coming, making the same mistakes, and so what I would do when they're doing their, you know, so I would kind of, I got into a habit of knowing what the right chords were, what the right changes were, what the right notes were, so that when I had to sit in for her, the student had no clue that I couldn't play.

124
00:17:32,000 --> 00:17:45,000
But I could say no, that's E sharp, you keep, you know, I mean, I'm sorry, that's E flat, you keep playing E natural, and that's why it doesn't work out, you got to play E flat, that's better.

125
00:17:45,000 --> 00:17:51,000
So I would sit there and the student would think, oh, this guy knows, you know, he's young, but he knows what he's doing.

126
00:17:51,000 --> 00:18:14,000
Well, her music influenced me, I was very interested in music when I was in high school, by the time I got to be a senior in high school, I was in the Simon Gratz High School choir, I used to direct it when Joy going Smith, who was our directoress, she was notoriously,

127
00:18:14,000 --> 00:18:34,000
may she rest in peace, but she was notoriously late whenever we had our concerts and recitals, and so, she was, I would be the one who would conduct the choir on those occasions when she was a half hour late and we needed to go on and do what we wanted to do.

128
00:18:35,000 --> 00:19:03,000
So I got very interested, I, in fact, I want a music scholarship to Temple University, and we had this group of teenagers who would sing, you know, we did pieces, in fact, we won summer, we put together the operetta,

129
00:19:03,000 --> 00:19:25,000
Gilbert and Sullivan's trial by jury, and we just kind of put it together and went up there in Germantown, I was still living in North Philly, but there was a Germantown women's club or something, there was a place where there was a stage, and we just did the whole thing, with the costumes, got people to come, it was a kind of fun thing.

130
00:19:25,000 --> 00:19:30,000
So that's one of my happy music memories. The other thing too is I started playing...

131
00:19:30,000 --> 00:19:35,000
It's a great studio for the business, I think, for the bells, Chinese, and the alley.

132
00:19:35,000 --> 00:19:44,000
Okay, we're back after a short break for the chiming of the clock. Dr. Chuchba, you were talking about the performance and moving towards Temple.

133
00:19:45,000 --> 00:20:07,000
Okay, I, I, I want a music scholarship to, to Temple University, on two grounds, I think, more so than my musical ability, because, because of my eyes, I didn't really see the notes on the paper very well, I'm extremely, I was, was extremely near-sighted.

134
00:20:08,000 --> 00:20:17,000
And, but I had a, I had a great ear, and if you played it, or I heard it, I could, I could get it.

135
00:20:18,000 --> 00:20:28,000
And I, I never formally, even though my mother tried to teach me, I, I learned how to read music by following the notes.

136
00:20:28,000 --> 00:20:36,000
I mean, it was, if there was a jump I jumped, I mean, I mean, and once I knew I was in the key, and if it wasn't, you know, if it wasn't,

137
00:20:36,000 --> 00:20:53,000
a flat that should be natural, or, you know, or, or, or a note that should be sharp, I mean, I could, I could pretty much, if, if I, if you gave me a piece of music, and I, and you started it, I could pretty much do it.

138
00:20:53,000 --> 00:21:02,000
And it, it, it appeared to people as if I could read extremely well, but I'm just using, using my head.

139
00:21:03,000 --> 00:21:07,000
And in fact, maybe reading music is just that. But anyway.

140
00:21:09,000 --> 00:21:11,000
It's like follow up 59, that you're starting a sample?

141
00:21:11,000 --> 00:21:12,000
Yeah.

142
00:21:12,000 --> 00:21:13,000
Follow up 59.

143
00:21:13,000 --> 00:21:24,000
So I went to Temple, and stayed there for about a year and a half, moved, left, I used, used the word, kwituated.

144
00:21:24,000 --> 00:21:34,000
I kwituated from Temple University, and had an opportunity to just move to New York and get away. I was about 19 at the time.

145
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:42,000
And it was time for me to leave Philly. I mean, I, what's a 19-year-old still living in his mother's house for? That didn't make any sense to me.

146
00:21:42,000 --> 00:21:53,000
So I moved out, and moved to New York, 318 East Forestry. I remember that, that address lived in the, in the East Village.

147
00:21:54,000 --> 00:21:58,000
It's called East Village now. It was lower East Side when I was there.

148
00:21:59,000 --> 00:22:05,000
And really, really loved it. It was, it was a whole new education.

149
00:22:05,000 --> 00:22:14,000
I mean, I ran into people who were Marxists and poets and musicians and artists and black nationalism.

150
00:22:14,000 --> 00:22:20,000
Just a whole range of people. I mean, I met French people and, you know, it's just a whole,

151
00:22:23,000 --> 00:22:31,000
group of people who were very different than people I grew up with. And, and it was just absolutely wonderful.

152
00:22:31,000 --> 00:22:45,000
I was just enamored. I was, you know, I'd go to the pink pussycat and, in, in the village and, and listen to poetry and, you know, go through the holes that it was just,

153
00:22:45,000 --> 00:22:55,000
it was having an honor at work and I tell you. And I met, met musicians and I used to do, while I was in New York.

154
00:22:55,000 --> 00:23:08,000
I did some playing. I was a jazz pianist and did some playing, but mostly I was listening and just kind of learning and kind of enjoying the thing.

155
00:23:08,000 --> 00:23:10,000
Absolutely. Go ahead.

156
00:23:10,000 --> 00:23:19,000
Would you have said before you arrived in New York, was your household a political house there for you, something of kind of a political kid?

157
00:23:19,000 --> 00:23:31,000
No, not really. I was the sort of the radical. I used to have these little discussions with my mother about the church, for example, as being gutless and irrelevant.

158
00:23:31,000 --> 00:23:40,000
And, and she, you know, her thing was, hey, I love Jesus. You know, you got any problems with him? You know, I agree with you 100% church is.

159
00:23:40,000 --> 00:23:51,000
So I mean, I couldn't do much arguing. You got any problems with Jesus personally? No, not really. But what Christians, yeah, I agree. Yeah, the crusades were horrible.

160
00:23:51,000 --> 00:24:01,000
Yeah, I mean, you know, he would not have sanctioned that. So that was the thing. And before I left, I guess I should say this on the religious side.

161
00:24:01,000 --> 00:24:20,000
When I was about 17 or 18, I became a Muslim and Ahmadiyyat Muslim. And say how cool my mom was. Her thing was, hey, whatever gets you to take a bath and put clean clothes on.

162
00:24:20,000 --> 00:24:45,000
I'm fine with it. So, so, um, she was, you know, you want to wash five times a day. Please, be my guest. So she was, she would let me, she would do some of the recipes that I'd learn, you know, get, and she'd cook them for me and enjoyed it.

163
00:24:45,000 --> 00:24:59,000
She was so comfortable in her own skin and in her own beliefs that her thing was explore, do what you need to do. And if, and if you can tell me Islam is better than Jesus, I'll switch.

164
00:24:59,000 --> 00:25:03,000
I mean, she was, that was her line.

165
00:25:03,000 --> 00:25:06,000
I had joined her towards Islam.

166
00:25:06,000 --> 00:25:25,000
I met a guy who was really sharp. He was young, maybe a year older than me. And he'd come around and he would talk about black history and he would talk about Islam and Islamic history and stuff that went on.

167
00:25:25,000 --> 00:25:50,000
And you know, it's like, wow, you mean the moors that I've read about were black people and they created the culture that is in Spain today when I look at all those beautiful things out of Spain that black people, you mean to tell me the stuff I read in my textbooks that blacks have not made any contribution to culture and the world, except for their dances and menstrual shows.

168
00:25:50,000 --> 00:26:01,000
Wow, that isn't so many. That was the catalyst. And it was, it was a different identity. It was, it was, it was fun.

169
00:26:01,000 --> 00:26:11,000
He was young, I was young and it, and by the way, my Muslim name is Yahya Abdul Hamid.

170
00:26:11,000 --> 00:26:25,000
And so that was who I was for a period. I'm very much John Elliott Church released, but I always give people credit for what they bring to my life and how they enrich my life.

171
00:26:25,000 --> 00:26:38,000
You'll find I'm very eclectic in my learnings and my appreciation for stuff. Anyway. So I did that and then I moved to New York and through all of this.

172
00:26:38,000 --> 00:26:48,000
And it was one of the reasons why I loved my mother so much. She was so open. She was never threatened by anything that I came up with.

173
00:26:48,000 --> 00:26:59,000
She was just very supportive of me. And after I, when I went, when I had been in New York for a while, I had this opportunity to go south. This is where the SNCC story starts.

174
00:26:59,000 --> 00:27:11,000
I had this opportunity. I was working at, as a janitor at Columbia Presbyterian Medical Center in Harlem.

175
00:27:11,000 --> 00:27:23,000
And there was, there was this bus that needed to go down to somewhere in Georgia, but it wasn't Atlanta.

176
00:27:23,000 --> 00:27:35,000
I know there was a SNCC was having some kind of retreat and the bus was supposed to be delivered to them. And I kind of lost my job.

177
00:27:35,000 --> 00:27:42,000
And there were people living in one of the negative sides of running into all these wonderful people that I met.

178
00:27:42,000 --> 00:27:53,000
People were always looking for a place to crash. They never paid rent. They just came, ate my food, stayed in the spot, brought their friends.

179
00:27:53,000 --> 00:28:02,000
And I was at a point where, you know, there were like five people in my apartment that I was responsible for the rent for.

180
00:28:02,000 --> 00:28:10,000
And it was rent control. I think it was something like 50 bucks a month. It was ridiculous. But anyway.

181
00:28:10,000 --> 00:28:18,000
I decided, I don't have anything to do. I'm not working. I'm not planning to go back to school now. I mean, sure, I'll get on the bus and take a ride.

182
00:28:18,000 --> 00:28:32,000
I mean, it was purely a matter of taking a ride. So I went with some other guys. And we went down. And when we got to Georgia, I was really impressed by the young people that I met, who were my age.

183
00:28:32,000 --> 00:28:42,000
And white and black in there, like all college students and they're talking about freedom, justice, inequality. And I'm like, okay, I can buy this.

184
00:28:42,000 --> 00:28:53,000
And so I hooked up with Reverend Charles Sherrod, who ran the Albany Park. In fact, I just heard a red that I believe he's still in Albany.

185
00:28:53,000 --> 00:29:08,000
I haven't seen him in many years, but I was under his tutelage and under his wing. I know I was a mess. But anyway, at the time I went and I went to Albany.

186
00:29:08,000 --> 00:29:20,000
We would, and I was assigned to Lee County and Terrell County. And later, I also worked in, and I don't remember what county it's in.

187
00:29:20,000 --> 00:29:28,000
I don't remember whether it's Lee or Terrell or some other county, but I worked in, it must be maybe a Sumter County, America. Is that in Sumter County?

188
00:29:28,000 --> 00:29:30,000
I'm not certain about that.

189
00:29:30,000 --> 00:29:32,000
Okay.

190
00:29:32,000 --> 00:29:38,000
I had, well, some interesting things that happened when I was with Snake. First of all,

191
00:29:38,000 --> 00:29:41,000
I'm going to lay out the carrot.

192
00:29:41,000 --> 00:29:50,000
Interesting things. Charles Sherrod was an interesting guy to begin with. And he was just die hard integrationist.

193
00:29:50,000 --> 00:29:56,000
I mean, he just, the whole motion of black and white together. So it was interesting with my experiences when I had been in New York,

194
00:29:56,000 --> 00:30:05,000
what I didn't mention, while I was in New York, and I had this Ahmadiyya Muslim background. And then when I got to New York,

195
00:30:05,000 --> 00:30:16,000
I would spend days and evenings up at 125 feet in 7th Avenue in front of Michelle's bookstore and listen to the nationalists give their speeches.

196
00:30:16,000 --> 00:30:28,000
And I met Malcolm X and I went to Temple Number 7 and stayed. And I was just so impressed. This guy was so brilliant.

197
00:30:28,000 --> 00:30:35,000
And that's nothing. I mean, I like smart people. I just, I love smart people anyway.

198
00:30:35,000 --> 00:30:43,000
And after the service was over, I went up to him and I said, Minister Malcolm, tell me about your life.

199
00:30:43,000 --> 00:30:54,000
And he said something that really, he said, my life is irrelevant. Where I've come from and where I am now is irrelevant.

200
00:30:54,000 --> 00:31:04,000
What matters is that we as people get our act together and forge ahead and do something for ourselves and stop waiting on other people to do things for us.

201
00:31:04,000 --> 00:31:14,000
And that just the humility. And he was hot stuff in terms of the press. I mean, everybody was vilifying him. But he was hot stop.

202
00:31:14,000 --> 00:31:28,000
I mean, everybody was, you know, Malcolm, Malcolm. And his whole demeanor was, I don't matter. Getting your head straight matters, getting the rest of my head together matter.

203
00:31:28,000 --> 00:31:36,000
And that just stuck, it just rang in my head. So when I went down to SNCC, I was a black nationalist by the time I went down to SNCC.

204
00:31:36,000 --> 00:31:45,000
And Shiraud understood you that way. He understood me that way. Yeah, I think, I think he understood me that way. Yeah, he had to because I had a white partner.

205
00:31:45,000 --> 00:31:59,000
And when I went out with my white partner to register people to vote, the black people that we dealt with would always look to the white partner because they were dealing with the power symbol.

206
00:31:59,000 --> 00:32:14,000
And from a purely ego centric point of view, it was bad enough to be in the north and ignored by white folk. And it was just intolerable to be ignored by my own folk.

207
00:32:14,000 --> 00:32:25,000
I could take it. So I went back to Charles, I said, look, man, I need a black partner. I don't want to do this with a white partner.

208
00:32:25,000 --> 00:32:35,000
And I had no problem. This was not personal. It was business. I mean, I loved every person that I met in SNCC.

209
00:32:35,000 --> 00:32:44,000
It wasn't that. It was that I needed to work with a black partner. And I had a way, I believed that I had a way of getting more young black people to register to vote.

210
00:32:44,000 --> 00:32:59,000
And so, Sherrod came up with this deal. If you can get more people, I'll let you do that. But if you can't register more people than you can with the partner that I gave you, you got to go back. I said, fine, I'll do that.

211
00:32:59,000 --> 00:33:10,000
So, I got a black partner. And that's when we start working in America. And at the time, this is really fun stuff here.

212
00:33:10,000 --> 00:33:22,000
At the time, if you can believe this, there was a gang war going on in America's Georgia. I mean, we're trying to register people to vote. And in the black community, you got these two teenage black gangs at war.

213
00:33:22,000 --> 00:33:30,000
And I just went in the middle of a gang fight and started screaming and hollering. You dumb.

214
00:33:30,000 --> 00:33:42,000
And they just stopped. I said, this is what white folks want you to do. Why are you doing this? We're here to help you to register so you can get some power for real. Stop fighting each.

215
00:33:42,000 --> 00:33:58,000
They stopped gang war. And we were able to recruit them to first register themselves. And then to negotiate a peace treaty and help us go out and recruit people to register and vote.

216
00:33:58,000 --> 00:34:05,000
If I had tried that, Norfolk would have been dead today. But anyway, so that was kind of a fun thing.

217
00:34:05,000 --> 00:34:19,000
So, oh man, that was, and it was the black talk. It was the black rap. It was the reason the rationale for voting is not to integrate.

218
00:34:19,000 --> 00:34:32,000
The rationale for voting is to build a power base so you can elect people who look like you to office, who will do for you, what people who don't look like you will do.

219
00:34:32,000 --> 00:34:46,000
And that, so that was, for me, that was the beginning of what I call black power. And that was not looked on lightly or nicely by the SNCC folks.

220
00:34:46,000 --> 00:34:59,000
But they tolerated me. And I give Charlie Sharad a great deal of respect for putting up with me given his own views.

221
00:34:59,000 --> 00:35:07,000
And I think that, and he was always, you know, you've rebelling. You rebelling.

222
00:35:07,000 --> 00:35:25,000
But he allowed me to be who I was. And so that was, you know, that was a success. I stayed with SNCC. Then there was the summer came up.

223
00:35:25,000 --> 00:35:37,000
The summer came up. The, the, where we're, where we're, where we're, where we're 64. No, that was 63.

224
00:35:37,000 --> 00:35:43,000
It had, or maybe was it early? I think it was, it wasn't 63.

225
00:35:43,000 --> 00:36:01,000
Yeah, because that's, because I believe, well, I must have come up after that. Anyway, I was in Mississippi doing, when did, um, lose?

226
00:36:01,000 --> 00:36:07,000
That was the later that was 65, because that was, that was on the way back from Montgomery after the summer.

227
00:36:07,000 --> 00:36:15,000
Okay, well, I wasn't there. I know my sense is that I left SNCC in 63. But anyway, I was in Mississippi.

228
00:36:15,000 --> 00:36:17,000
That's what your, that's what your printed resume said.

229
00:36:17,000 --> 00:36:26,000
Yeah. Well, you know, I mean, I may have the, but I, I know that I was in Philly by the summer of 64. I know that.

230
00:36:26,000 --> 00:36:36,000
I know that I was in Mississippi at the Kofo Freedom School teaching literacy in Greenwood, Mississippi. I know I was there.

231
00:36:36,000 --> 00:36:48,000
And I think the reason that we were sent there was because there was an assault. And I'm thinking it was the three civil rights workers that caused us to move in, because we were moving in.

232
00:36:48,000 --> 00:36:55,000
I thought after that. But, you know, my, my, yeah. Well, anyway, there was, there was stuff that went on.

233
00:36:55,000 --> 00:37:00,000
No matter, before you, before we ship to Greenwood, because I want to ask, tell me a little bit more. I want to ask,

234
00:37:00,000 --> 00:37:08,000
Southwestern, how, Southwest Georgia was mean and nasty, hard. Yeah. And you guys were in the thick of, yeah.

235
00:37:08,000 --> 00:37:12,000
A lot of difficult stuff. Yes. Terrible violence. Absolutely.

236
00:37:12,000 --> 00:37:17,000
How did you manage through that? How did you, um, tell yourself to get up in the morning?

237
00:37:18,000 --> 00:37:22,000
Well, it was easy to get up in the morning. Fear will get you up.

238
00:37:22,000 --> 00:37:35,000
I was never, I have never been so scared. In fact, I blame my high blood pressure on my experiences in Southwest Georgia.

239
00:37:36,000 --> 00:37:43,000
Um, it was, it was scary, but at the same time, here's what's so awesome.

240
00:37:43,000 --> 00:37:52,000
When you're with people who are committed to something that's good, and you're not the only one who's afraid,

241
00:37:52,000 --> 00:38:01,000
everybody's scared, you start singing. I mean, for the time I was there, Jesus was the man. You understand?

242
00:38:02,000 --> 00:38:08,000
I was a Muslim, but I did not pray to Allah when I was in Southwest Georgia. I prayed to Jesus.

243
00:38:08,000 --> 00:38:17,000
I had no, in fact, I had to nerve, and one, um, at one church meeting,

244
00:38:17,000 --> 00:38:24,000
I deacon prayed some, some nonsense, and I stood up and I said, you know, we're in this real situation,

245
00:38:25,000 --> 00:38:31,000
and you are, you don't believe what you're talking about. You know, I'm not just kind of castigated this guy.

246
00:38:31,000 --> 00:38:36,000
I mean, you know, young, arrogant kids will do that to you all the time.

247
00:38:36,000 --> 00:38:47,000
Um, but anyway, I kind of castigated him for, you know, and offered instead a real prayer based on fear,

248
00:38:47,000 --> 00:38:54,000
and look, God helped us. The clan was outside. Talking about burning the church down,

249
00:38:54,000 --> 00:39:01,000
we don't need the old father God in whom the world, no, we need help, you know, get it real.

250
00:39:01,000 --> 00:39:09,000
Get to the point. God knows what that is. So that was interesting. That was an interesting experience.

251
00:39:09,000 --> 00:39:21,000
But yeah, the whole crew, I always separated my ideological concerns about blacks and whites from my personal stuff.

252
00:39:21,000 --> 00:39:30,000
It was never personal for me. I love people, you know, and, but anyway, good.

253
00:39:30,000 --> 00:39:35,000
In this time, did you develop a sense of an opinion about SCLC and Rung King?

254
00:39:35,000 --> 00:39:36,000
Oh, God, yes.

255
00:39:36,000 --> 00:39:44,000
Well, I mean, as part of it because of youth and part of it because, I mean, as far as I was concerned,

256
00:39:44,000 --> 00:39:53,000
Martin was, you know, he was too easy, he was too light, he was not on point.

257
00:39:53,000 --> 00:40:00,000
Well, part of my anger, which I picked up from, Snick folks, was, here we are in Albany trying to clean up after his mess.

258
00:40:00,000 --> 00:40:10,000
He wouldn't even stay because it wasn't working. Snick stayed and continue to try to work when the cameras weren't there.

259
00:40:10,000 --> 00:40:23,000
And so that was a source of, in fact, I have to admit that it was only at his death that I was wondering why I was mourning so much.

260
00:40:23,000 --> 00:40:30,000
Because I always held against my issues with him about Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party and the role that he played,

261
00:40:30,000 --> 00:40:37,000
and trying to get them to line up to the Democratic Party and not let them do what they needed to do.

262
00:40:37,000 --> 00:40:46,000
So, I had real issues. It was only at his death that I said, oh, God, this was my brother.

263
00:40:46,000 --> 00:40:58,000
And I may disagree with his tactics, but, you know, unfortunately, I got to respect him after his demise,

264
00:40:58,000 --> 00:41:02,000
but had very little respect for him prior to it.

265
00:41:02,000 --> 00:41:12,000
We have a little bit of a little bit.

266
00:41:12,000 --> 00:41:17,000
Okay, we're back after a short break.

267
00:41:17,000 --> 00:41:29,000
Can you tell me a little bit more about some of the things that stand out in your memory about the people you met in Southwest Georgia and the communities you went into?

268
00:41:29,000 --> 00:41:40,000
Yeah, I think the communities that most affected me, well, first of all, I fell in love with the people in Albany.

269
00:41:40,000 --> 00:41:50,000
I remember our mass meetings on Monday nights if I'm not mistaken, again, but it was one regular night every week.

270
00:41:50,000 --> 00:42:12,000
And there was one time when a preacher came to the meeting, and he started talking about the fact that the governor had given him a letter that allows him to travel anywhere in Georgia on the roads and not be less than he can give it to the Georgia State Police or something happened.

271
00:42:12,000 --> 00:42:20,000
And somebody in the crowd, and I think it was Charlie Sherrods watching.

272
00:42:20,000 --> 00:42:26,000
And then he started talking some more, and then you heard another watching.

273
00:42:26,000 --> 00:42:29,000
And it was sort of like knowing that this is a plan.

274
00:42:29,000 --> 00:42:33,000
Here's a guy that's trying to tell us cease and desist.

275
00:42:33,000 --> 00:42:39,000
And so different people would say different things, and different times as he's talking.

276
00:42:39,000 --> 00:42:46,000
So that it's more and more clear that this guy is on the other side.

277
00:42:46,000 --> 00:42:49,000
He's just sitting in here to try to keep us from doing.

278
00:42:49,000 --> 00:42:56,000
And then we just started singing, and we sang whatever the song was, and just drowned him out.

279
00:42:56,000 --> 00:43:04,000
The whole church ain't gonna let nobody turn me around.

280
00:43:04,000 --> 00:43:07,000
And we went right into it.

281
00:43:07,000 --> 00:43:12,000
And it's still a favorite song of mine.

282
00:43:12,000 --> 00:43:17,000
And he just went and sat down.

283
00:43:17,000 --> 00:43:20,000
So that was the thing.

284
00:43:20,000 --> 00:43:29,000
The other thing in terms of community, you would think that the people who made the change

285
00:43:29,000 --> 00:43:34,000
and who had the guts in those communities were the young people.

286
00:43:34,000 --> 00:43:36,000
It was not so.

287
00:43:36,000 --> 00:43:41,000
It was the older folks who were determined that they would not have their children and grandchildren

288
00:43:41,000 --> 00:43:44,000
and live the life that they lived.

289
00:43:44,000 --> 00:43:49,000
And it used to make me angry that the kids didn't want to hear what we were talking about.

290
00:43:49,000 --> 00:43:51,000
By and large, except for America.

291
00:43:51,000 --> 00:43:54,000
America was a special case.

292
00:43:54,000 --> 00:43:59,000
But the kids in the communities that we were dead didn't want to be bothered.

293
00:43:59,000 --> 00:44:06,000
Older grandmothers would listen to us and would want the best for their kids and their grandkids

294
00:44:06,000 --> 00:44:10,000
and they were the ones who were taking the risks.

295
00:44:10,000 --> 00:44:14,000
I remember one incident that really upset me.

296
00:44:14,000 --> 00:44:17,000
I've never really gotten over it.

297
00:44:17,000 --> 00:44:21,000
We were in one community in southwest Georgia.

298
00:44:21,000 --> 00:44:27,000
And I don't even remember whether it was Lee County, Terrell County, somewhere.

299
00:44:27,000 --> 00:44:35,000
And we were called out to this house where the mother told us that the sheriff,

300
00:44:35,000 --> 00:44:44,000
who was notorious, Dunnoway, was just a notorious horrendous guy.

301
00:44:44,000 --> 00:44:54,000
He had grabbed her son who worked in a white store doing something.

302
00:44:54,000 --> 00:45:06,000
And the baker, a bakery truck driver, had raped the boy's sister.

303
00:45:06,000 --> 00:45:13,000
The sheriff, and I guess the boy tried to tell the sheriff or tried to tell,

304
00:45:13,000 --> 00:45:17,000
the sheriff pulled out a gun, put it to the boy's head, and said,

305
00:45:17,000 --> 00:45:22,000
if you open your mouth about this, I'll blow your head off.

306
00:45:22,000 --> 00:45:29,000
And I will tell the guy you're working for that you molested his daughter.

307
00:45:29,000 --> 00:45:37,000
And I was livid in the feeling of not being able to do anything that the law,

308
00:45:37,000 --> 00:45:44,000
the person who represents the law, you just, how can you go to the sheriff who says,

309
00:45:44,000 --> 00:45:49,000
I'll kill you. And the other side of it is, I won't kill you.

310
00:45:49,000 --> 00:45:54,000
I'll let the guy who's, who's, you'll be lynched.

311
00:45:54,000 --> 00:46:01,000
And I remember feeling that pain and that, that angst, that rage.

312
00:46:01,000 --> 00:46:03,000
And there was nowhere I could put it.

313
00:46:03,000 --> 00:46:08,000
There was nothing we could, we couldn't tell the other frustrating things

314
00:46:08,000 --> 00:46:11,000
when the FBI guys would come down.

315
00:46:11,000 --> 00:46:15,000
They did nothing. You could talk to them. They went back and told the sheriff,

316
00:46:15,000 --> 00:46:22,000
whatever you said. They weren't trying to protect you. They were, they had no interest.

317
00:46:22,000 --> 00:46:29,000
It was just very frustrating to work in a situation where all you had was your colleagues.

318
00:46:29,000 --> 00:46:33,000
The only people who believed in what it was that you believed in, and the people.

319
00:46:33,000 --> 00:46:38,000
And again, I go back to that thing. One of the things that kept me in,

320
00:46:38,000 --> 00:46:45,000
I was scared enough to run the first day. I've always told people that I have a back problem.

321
00:46:45,000 --> 00:46:51,000
And if you look at it, you'll see a yellow streak all the way.

322
00:46:51,000 --> 00:46:57,000
But I felt, I can leave, but they can.

323
00:46:57,000 --> 00:47:02,000
You know, I can't, at this point, I just can't, I'll be scared with them

324
00:47:02,000 --> 00:47:05,000
because they have a lot more to lose than I do.

325
00:47:05,000 --> 00:47:10,000
But I remember that, and that was extremely frustrating, extremely frustrating.

326
00:47:10,000 --> 00:47:16,000
And we'd hear about atrocities every day that never came to the light of day.

327
00:47:16,000 --> 00:47:19,000
And we'd hear about them and people would tell us about them.

328
00:47:19,000 --> 00:47:24,000
Some things we'd even see, and there'd be nothing you could do.

329
00:47:24,000 --> 00:47:28,000
So that was the, that was the gripper.

330
00:47:28,000 --> 00:47:32,000
We moved on to Mississippi from South America, Georgia.

331
00:47:32,000 --> 00:47:39,000
Did you go in a mood of, and bivalence about your prospects?

332
00:47:39,000 --> 00:47:43,000
America's been something of a success, and you go forward.

333
00:47:43,000 --> 00:47:49,000
But all this other is pattern of wallessness and violence.

334
00:47:49,000 --> 00:47:51,000
Dispare.

335
00:47:51,000 --> 00:47:54,000
What was your, what was your mood that you took with you to, and the Mississippi,

336
00:47:54,000 --> 00:47:58,000
your perspective on this, this style of effort to change things?

337
00:47:58,000 --> 00:48:08,000
Well, I was really, let me just say this to you, there were two strains that were going on in SNCC.

338
00:48:08,000 --> 00:48:11,000
Two camps.

339
00:48:11,000 --> 00:48:18,000
There was a direct action camp, which was focused around demonstration sit-ins.

340
00:48:18,000 --> 00:48:21,000
And then there was the voter registration camp.

341
00:48:21,000 --> 00:48:27,000
I chose the voter registration camp because I saw that as a way out.

342
00:48:27,000 --> 00:48:32,000
I couldn't see demonstrating as a way out.

343
00:48:32,000 --> 00:48:35,000
I saw no future in demonstrating.

344
00:48:35,000 --> 00:48:38,000
I couldn't see myself getting beat in the head for nothing.

345
00:48:38,000 --> 00:48:41,000
If I'm getting beaten ahead because I'm trying to get people registered to vote,

346
00:48:41,000 --> 00:48:48,000
at least there's something, but to get beaten ahead to eat some food that somebody's probably spinning,

347
00:48:48,000 --> 00:48:51,000
I couldn't, that just didn't come back.

348
00:48:51,000 --> 00:48:54,000
So, I was happy to be involved.

349
00:48:54,000 --> 00:49:01,000
I mean, I was appalled that black folks had to take a constitutional test.

350
00:49:01,000 --> 00:49:05,000
And my god, lawyers can't understand the constitution.

351
00:49:05,000 --> 00:49:15,000
You can get all, I mean, there are experts in constitutional law who disagree about what something means.

352
00:49:15,000 --> 00:49:21,000
So, but it was a challenge to just work with what I could work with.

353
00:49:21,000 --> 00:49:26,000
It's like when you're in an impossible situation, this is another lesson that I learned.

354
00:49:26,000 --> 00:49:31,000
When you're in an impossible situation, you just do what's in front of you.

355
00:49:31,000 --> 00:49:33,000
I mean, I couldn't even think about future.

356
00:49:33,000 --> 00:49:35,000
I couldn't think about where is this going.

357
00:49:35,000 --> 00:49:37,000
It was just, I'm here right now.

358
00:49:37,000 --> 00:49:39,000
These folks are here right now.

359
00:49:39,000 --> 00:49:41,000
I'm going to give them the best I got.

360
00:49:41,000 --> 00:49:42,000
I want to encourage them.

361
00:49:42,000 --> 00:49:43,000
I'm going to help them.

362
00:49:43,000 --> 00:49:50,000
I mean, I didn't even think through to, even if they know that the right answer is the people when they take the test, they're going to tell them you got it wrong.

363
00:49:50,000 --> 00:49:52,000
I didn't even go there.

364
00:49:52,000 --> 00:49:54,000
It was like, give them what you have.

365
00:49:54,000 --> 00:49:55,000
Give it all you got.

366
00:49:55,000 --> 00:50:00,000
And just, it's like, put one foot in front of the other.

367
00:50:00,000 --> 00:50:01,000
Don't think about the outcome.

368
00:50:01,000 --> 00:50:03,000
Don't worry about the end of the road.

369
00:50:03,000 --> 00:50:04,000
Just take steps.

370
00:50:04,000 --> 00:50:06,000
And that's what was my mindset.

371
00:50:06,000 --> 00:50:11,000
And I was quite, I had consoled myself with this.

372
00:50:12,000 --> 00:50:25,000
I was quite, I guess in the real sense, that was probably one of my snake experience was probably the first time I was living in the moment.

373
00:50:25,000 --> 00:50:28,000
Before then and after then, I've always thought about what's next.

374
00:50:28,000 --> 00:50:31,000
Where is this going?

375
00:50:31,000 --> 00:50:32,000
Where is it leading?

376
00:50:32,000 --> 00:50:33,000
What's the end game?

377
00:50:33,000 --> 00:50:35,000
I'm always thinking about it right now.

378
00:50:35,000 --> 00:50:39,000
I'm thinking about what's the, not for this, but other things that I'm involved in.

379
00:50:40,000 --> 00:50:41,000
Where am I going?

380
00:50:41,000 --> 00:50:42,000
And where is the end game?

381
00:50:42,000 --> 00:50:45,000
And how do I make steps to guarantee that I get there?

382
00:50:45,000 --> 00:50:50,000
But in Southwest Georgia and Mississippi, I got the privilege, and I can say it now looking back,

383
00:50:50,000 --> 00:50:53,000
the privilege of actually living in the moment.

384
00:50:53,000 --> 00:50:55,000
I couldn't go beyond that moment.

385
00:50:55,000 --> 00:50:57,000
I had to live every minute of it.

386
00:50:57,000 --> 00:51:01,000
And was, was, was satisfied to do that.

387
00:51:01,000 --> 00:51:08,000
Was Mississippi, in essence, a continuation of the same type of experience or in substantial shape?

388
00:51:08,000 --> 00:51:14,000
Well, the difference was, of course, that I wasn't doing direct getting people to go down to the polls.

389
00:51:14,000 --> 00:51:18,000
I was teaching people literacy.

390
00:51:18,000 --> 00:51:25,000
And it was, it was just a different, a different mode.

391
00:51:25,000 --> 00:51:28,000
And one that I quite liked.

392
00:51:28,000 --> 00:51:32,000
In fact, that got me when I came back to Philadelphia.

393
00:51:32,000 --> 00:51:34,000
I started a school.

394
00:51:34,000 --> 00:51:38,000
That was sort of my introduction to, hey, you like teaching.

395
00:51:38,000 --> 00:51:40,000
Why don't you do it?

396
00:51:40,000 --> 00:51:46,000
One more question about all that before you turn, turn our focus towards Philadelphia.

397
00:51:46,000 --> 00:51:52,000
Are there folks who stand out, you can mention Reverend Sherrod or are there other folks who stand out?

398
00:51:52,000 --> 00:51:56,000
I'm also interested in, of course, the interesting gender and racial dynamics,

399
00:51:56,000 --> 00:52:00,000
because you get some white volunteers, you get some women in the mix, and interesting thoughts,

400
00:52:00,000 --> 00:52:02,000
you think that coming?

401
00:52:02,000 --> 00:52:10,000
Yeah, well, Sherrod sticks out, Diane Nash Bevel,

402
00:52:10,000 --> 00:52:17,000
who was just sort of the sweetheart of the movement.

403
00:52:17,000 --> 00:52:31,000
Bernice Reagan, who was not only singing, but brought something to the movement.

404
00:52:31,000 --> 00:52:39,000
Bernice sticks out, Faith Holtzart, who was in our camp.

405
00:52:39,000 --> 00:52:49,000
Sticks out, Bob Mance, who I worked with, who was, I'm telling you, sticks out.

406
00:52:49,000 --> 00:52:53,000
And again, you're dealing with a memory.

407
00:52:53,000 --> 00:53:03,000
Man, 50 years ago, but there are certain people who, and I'm trying to think,

408
00:53:03,000 --> 00:53:09,000
when this is all over and you're going, I will remember other names.

409
00:53:09,000 --> 00:53:17,000
But those are people who, and then there were community folks,

410
00:53:17,000 --> 00:53:21,000
Eddie, whose last name I don't remember, but I worked with Eddie.

411
00:53:21,000 --> 00:53:25,000
Eddie put up with a lot of this from me.

412
00:53:25,000 --> 00:53:28,000
I teased him a lot.

413
00:53:28,000 --> 00:53:36,000
I won't tell that story, but anyway.

414
00:53:36,000 --> 00:53:44,000
But there were, oh well, Dory Ladner and Joyce Ladner.

415
00:53:44,000 --> 00:53:48,000
It just comes.

416
00:53:48,000 --> 00:53:54,000
But there were just, they were,

417
00:53:54,000 --> 00:54:02,000
and John Lewis, and I'll say this, what I disagreed with John Lewis's view,

418
00:54:02,000 --> 00:54:13,000
but I respected him because he, if you awaken John at three o'clock in the morning

419
00:54:13,000 --> 00:54:20,000
and ask him what his principles were, he would tell you whether he was asleep, awake,

420
00:54:20,000 --> 00:54:28,000
he would say what he had to say, he would stick by it, and no matter what criticism he got,

421
00:54:28,000 --> 00:54:32,000
he would not come back at you, he would let you do that.

422
00:54:32,000 --> 00:54:42,000
And I just, and to this day, I respect John, I mean, John Lewis would have to do something absolutely horrendous.

423
00:54:42,000 --> 00:54:45,000
I mean, he'd have to do something.

424
00:54:45,000 --> 00:54:47,000
I mean, he'd have to kill 50,000 people.

425
00:54:47,000 --> 00:54:52,000
And the first few people he killed, I said, well, you know, you got to be some residual one.

426
00:54:52,000 --> 00:54:58,000
But he would have to really do something, really atrocious for me to say, that's not the John Lewis.

427
00:54:58,000 --> 00:55:04,000
I know, I, he was a kind of weird inspiration.

428
00:55:04,000 --> 00:55:11,000
I disagreed with his views, his view about us together.

429
00:55:11,000 --> 00:55:15,000
No, we're so full of force, I like that, but it, it, it's just the integration.

430
00:55:15,000 --> 00:55:26,000
I had, issue, I saw a difference between justice and integration was not necessary.

431
00:55:26,000 --> 00:55:34,000
I saw justice as necessary and justice, and people can choose to integrate on a personal level, that's fine.

432
00:55:34,000 --> 00:55:45,000
And, but the, the economy has to be open to people and people need to have, you know, opportunities to live their lives without being held out.

433
00:55:45,000 --> 00:55:48,000
But that's not integration, that's economic justice.

434
00:55:48,000 --> 00:55:52,000
And so I had, you know, I'm a category person.

435
00:55:52,000 --> 00:56:00,000
So I had separate categories, but what I loved about John is that he was passionate.

436
00:56:00,000 --> 00:56:07,000
I mean, this was stuff, not, this wasn't a script that he, he didn't say what he said because the cameras were there.

437
00:56:07,000 --> 00:56:11,000
This is, this guy talked this stuff when he's sitting alone with you.

438
00:56:11,000 --> 00:56:18,000
He said the same thing in front of the cameras, he would not back off, he would say what, and I just respected him for that.

439
00:56:18,000 --> 00:56:21,000
And loved him for that.

440
00:56:21,000 --> 00:56:28,000
So he's a guy that, which shows you can disagree with somebody and really, really respect them.

441
00:56:28,000 --> 00:56:31,000
And, and he's want to take my hat off to still.

442
00:56:31,000 --> 00:56:37,000
What, what collection of factors drew you back towards front open since you picked?

443
00:56:37,000 --> 00:56:41,000
Ah, here comes the other story.

444
00:56:41,000 --> 00:56:47,000
There was a point that I got in, Nick, where I, it was like, look, this is not working for me.

445
00:56:47,000 --> 00:56:57,000
This is not, I went back to Atlanta, and there I joined the Nation of Islam and became a black Muslim this time.

446
00:56:57,000 --> 00:57:07,000
And I joined the mosque in Atlanta, and I was, I was trying to recruit sneak people to the mosque.

447
00:57:07,000 --> 00:57:20,000
And Jeremiah X was the minister there, and I immediately started trying to do some organizing in Atlanta in a place called buttermilk bottom.

448
00:57:20,000 --> 00:57:27,000
At the time, buttermilk bottom had no paving on the street, the very poor black community.

449
00:57:27,000 --> 00:57:39,000
And my theory was, because I was a true believer in the sense that I felt that the black Muslims could do, were, were exactly what black people needed.

450
00:57:39,000 --> 00:57:46,000
They needed to focus on developing themselves and stop trying to be nice to white folks.

451
00:57:46,000 --> 00:57:49,000
Let's just do what we need to do.

452
00:57:49,000 --> 00:57:55,000
And so I, I was active in trying to organize buttermilk bottom.

453
00:57:55,000 --> 00:57:57,000
And for the mosque?

454
00:57:57,000 --> 00:58:05,000
Yeah, well, actually it was, when I say for the mosque, it was, yeah, I guess it was.

455
00:58:05,000 --> 00:58:14,000
And Jeremiah was very open to my ideas, because my thing was, look man, we don't need to have everybody being black Muslims.

456
00:58:14,000 --> 00:58:17,000
That's not, shouldn't be our goal to recruit everybody.

457
00:58:17,000 --> 00:58:33,000
We need communities in Atlanta who will stand up for us, so that when you make a pronouncement, and the press starts messing with you, you've got community people who say, hey, we think he's a great guy, and we support what he has to say, and that will make them back off.

458
00:58:33,000 --> 00:58:39,000
And so he said, okay, he let me do that. And so what I try to do was to develop some kind of small little economic program.

459
00:58:39,000 --> 00:58:44,000
I hated Selim Muhammad's speech newspaper. I like Selim Muhammad's paper, I've never been a salesman.

460
00:58:44,000 --> 00:58:52,000
I tried and failed miserably, both in insurance and something in securities. But anyway.

461
00:58:52,000 --> 00:59:00,000
So I tried to organize young people, and I had to get permission from the Chicago headquarters.

462
00:59:00,000 --> 00:59:05,000
And when I tried to get permission from Chicago, I was turned down.

463
00:59:06,000 --> 00:59:15,000
And that's when I first started feeling funny, because we're like, wait a minute, then you're not what you're advertised to be.

464
00:59:15,000 --> 00:59:21,000
Because I came on the advertisement that you care about us, and you want to see us develop.

465
00:59:21,000 --> 00:59:29,000
And we're talking about businesses, and we have an opportunity where we can give kids, they can sell papers and make money.

466
00:59:29,000 --> 00:59:37,000
I don't need to do that, I can work at something else. I'm not selling papers to make money, I'm selling papers to get the word out.

467
00:59:37,000 --> 00:59:47,000
So in the meantime, I met some, I started going to Atlanta University and talking to people, and trying to recruit college students for the month.

468
00:59:47,000 --> 00:59:59,000
And my view was a little bit with my friend DuVois, and we got a talented tent that we needed to have.

469
00:59:59,000 --> 01:00:10,000
So I was able to work, and we got some other professionals in the mosque, which I thought was a kind of big deal.

470
01:00:10,000 --> 01:00:16,000
And we gave three of them and me got together. I was nowhere near where these guys were.

471
01:00:16,000 --> 01:00:22,000
We had a mathematician, we had an economist, the guy was working on his PhD in the economics.

472
01:00:22,000 --> 01:00:28,000
And I forget right now what the other one was.

473
01:00:28,000 --> 01:00:33,000
But I mean, these are guys who have studied, and who are at the university, and who are Muslims.

474
01:00:33,000 --> 01:00:39,000
And they came up with a project to just be a little bit more proactive.

475
01:00:39,000 --> 01:00:48,000
We've got an opportunity here. We had Jeremiah, so when anything happened in Atlanta, the press would come over to Jeremiah, what do you say?

476
01:00:48,000 --> 01:00:54,000
I mean, that was like a big deal in those days. So we'll listen to these other people, but we want to hear what you have to say.

477
01:00:54,000 --> 01:01:01,000
And so anyway, these guys came up with this proposal and flew it up to, I mean, I expected mine to go down. I mean, who am I?

478
01:01:01,000 --> 01:01:10,000
These guys flew it up to Chicago and it got shot down. And at that moment, I continued to be a Muslim.

479
01:01:10,000 --> 01:01:20,000
I loved Jeremiah because he was just a good guy. He had, he was very personable. I mean, I'd hear him preach and say certain things.

480
01:01:20,000 --> 01:01:27,000
And then we would talk privately. And he was just, he was just a good guy.

481
01:01:27,000 --> 01:01:35,000
So at that point, I was losing interest in the black Muslim movement and ready to come back to Philly.

482
01:01:35,000 --> 01:01:48,000
And it just so happened, it just sort of happens, that he got transferred. They wanted somebody else who he didn't like to take over Atlanta after he had built it up.

483
01:01:48,000 --> 01:01:57,000
We doubled the size of the mosque. And he got sent to Philadelphia. It was just natural. He said, hey, John, come with me back to Philly.

484
01:01:57,000 --> 01:02:02,000
I'll make you, because I was Secretary of the mosque down there. I'll make you Secretary of the mosque. It'll be okay.

485
01:02:02,000 --> 01:02:09,000
I came, come back to Philly with that in mind. And what happened politically, there was somebody else who was the Secretary here.

486
01:02:09,000 --> 01:02:19,000
And then the politics, Jeremiah had to, and I know he didn't just tell me that, because he was really straight with me. He would tell me, look man, I don't remember one time.

487
01:02:19,000 --> 01:02:28,000
I got very emotional about the messenger. And I was talking about how wonderful he was. He said, he said, John, get a grip.

488
01:02:28,000 --> 01:02:44,000
John, you're not going to lie to me, you're just a guy. Don't tell anybody I told you. Don't get carried away.

489
01:02:44,000 --> 01:02:57,000
And that he would tell me that. I just appreciated his honesty. So I knew when he told me you'll be Secretary, when he got back, he came to my mother's back.

490
01:02:57,000 --> 01:03:10,000
I said, I'm back at my mother's and he said, John, I can't make you Secretary. The messenger wants the guy that's there to stay. It's out of my hand.

491
01:03:10,000 --> 01:03:19,000
So I said, okay. And immediately, I think I was back in town, maybe a week or two, and I hooked up with the Northern Student Movement.

492
01:03:19,000 --> 01:03:32,000
I mean, I had to be, and I went to North Philly, and I was familiar with North Philly, and I went over to an area of North Philly that I hadn't been in before around Ridge Avenue, Ridge and Jefferson.

493
01:03:32,000 --> 01:03:48,000
And there was a building available, and I said, hey, we need to come up with a project in the Northern Student Movement that is a library, we call it Freedom Library, NSM Freedom Library, which will have books buying about black people.

494
01:03:48,000 --> 01:04:01,000
Because my argument was the reason that black people are not functioning the way they should is because they have little self-esteem, they don't know their history, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah.

495
01:04:01,000 --> 01:04:16,000
And at this point, I had completely discounted the whole notion of racism. I mean, I didn't address it that way. I mean, just all my meetings with my communist colleagues didn't help me with that.

496
01:04:16,000 --> 01:04:21,000
I was busy dealing with other issues, but anyway.

497
01:04:21,000 --> 01:04:45,000
So I put in a proposal, I went to the Dolphinger McMahon Foundation, and asked for a grant that same summer, there was a riot in North Philadelphia, and every store on Ridge Avenue got broken into except Freedom Library.

498
01:04:45,000 --> 01:05:05,000
That, because it was a storefront, and we had to globe with hands around it, and it just said NSM Freedom Library, and it wasn't attacked, which was just kind of interesting, because they got the Barber Shop next door. Why are you going to hit the Barber Shop, but anyway.

499
01:05:05,000 --> 01:05:16,000
So after the riots, Dolphinger McMahon came through with a $1,200 grant. I guess it was a lot of money in those days. I don't remember.

500
01:05:16,000 --> 01:05:34,000
And then, that was like 64. So when I left the nation, I was still in the mosque, but I was not active. I mean, I'd go on Sundays, I supported Minister Jeremiah,

501
01:05:34,000 --> 01:05:47,000
because he was a friend, he was a really good guy. And then the stuff happened, and I'm kind of fuzzy about the dates, but Malcolm had left or left?

502
01:05:47,000 --> 01:05:50,000
I'd left the spring and six years ago.

503
01:05:50,000 --> 01:05:57,000
And so I went up to New York, I met with him, Malcolm.

504
01:05:57,000 --> 01:06:08,000
Oh yeah, oh yeah. And it's like, okay, let me help hook up the Philly chapter, and the guys.

505
01:06:08,000 --> 01:06:25,000
Anyway, people I met in Philly who was supposed to be part of this thing were, I don't know who they were, I'm not going to say they were agents, I'm not going to say they were the shakiest people I had ever met.

506
01:06:25,000 --> 01:06:30,000
So, you were supposed to be associated with Malcolm.

507
01:06:30,000 --> 01:06:42,000
And so anyway, I joined the Organization of African American Unity, and I was supposed to put a picture of Malcolm in the window.

508
01:06:42,000 --> 01:06:49,000
Well, when I did that and word got back to Jeremiah, he went to my mother and he said, please tell your son.

509
01:06:49,000 --> 01:06:59,000
I mean, that was the time when if you got out of the Nation of Islam and followed Malcolm, you were writing a death sentence for yourself, you won't get yourself hurt.

510
01:06:59,000 --> 01:07:07,000
Well, I'm glad that Jeremiah was my friend, because he told the people of the food of Islam, don't touch him.

511
01:07:07,000 --> 01:07:14,000
And he begged my mother, please talk to John, don't let him continue with this stuff, he could get hurt.

512
01:07:14,000 --> 01:07:22,000
And he was pacing up and down. She told me when I talked to her about it later, he was pacing up and down the floor.

513
01:07:22,000 --> 01:07:28,000
I can't be there to protect him every step of the way, you know.

514
01:07:28,000 --> 01:07:41,000
So, the mosque had lent me chairs, had given me chairs and tables for the Freedom Library and they just came and took them back.

515
01:07:41,000 --> 01:07:45,000
But they didn't touch the building, they didn't touch me, they followed orders, which I saw.

516
01:07:45,000 --> 01:07:52,000
So, to this day, even though minister Jeremiah has passed away, he's another guy who I absolutely love, respect.

517
01:07:52,000 --> 01:08:01,000
I got to tell you one of the incident with him that comes up later, there was a time when I converted to Christianity.

518
01:08:01,000 --> 01:08:04,000
It was around 66.

519
01:08:04,000 --> 01:08:19,000
So, yeah, it's within that timeframe, but two years later, because that was 66, I converted, but this was like a personal conversion type thing, where I had an encounter, where I realized that,

520
01:08:19,000 --> 01:08:26,000
Jesus was real and it was really, I wasn't in church, I mean, this is a house in my house.

521
01:08:26,000 --> 01:08:33,000
But it came a time when I had to debate Jeremiah X.

522
01:08:33,000 --> 01:08:48,000
And it was the funniest debate that you ever want to see, because I stood up there and talked about how all the good things I learned from the honorable Elijah Muhammad, how great Jeremiah X was, what a friend he was.

523
01:08:48,000 --> 01:09:09,000
I mean, I just told the truth, I learned so much from the, I mean, every encounter, I mean, I don't leave an organization and then trash it, because there was good stuff that I learned, I learned about myself, I learned about possibilities for us that I would never have gotten any other, never would have gotten it in church for heaven's sake.

524
01:09:09,000 --> 01:09:32,000
And so, at that debate, I just talked about, I just preached Jesus, basically, and said, hey, the honorable Elijah Muhammad is good, when I was a Muslim, I believed in, in a law with all my heart and soul, but I didn't have an internal witness or knowledge that God was with me.

525
01:09:32,000 --> 01:09:49,000
And so, when Jeremiah got up, I mean, this is a public scenario, and the fruit of Islam is standing around wanting to hurt me, because how dare I debate with it, I don't know who set the debate up, I didn't.

526
01:09:49,000 --> 01:10:15,000
And Jeremiah stood up and he said, he said two things, one, I should tell you this before, before we had the debate, I called Jeremiah when I had, because he knew I was out of the nation at this point, and I called him up and told him about why Jesus experienced, and he said to me, he said, John, because of a friend, he said, if I knew, Jesus was what you told me, he is now, I never would have trashed him the way I did.

527
01:10:15,000 --> 01:10:41,000
I mean, that's just the level of respect between us, he knew I wasn't playing, and so anyway, when we had the debate, the major argument he made was, he said, this is the first time we have had a Muslim to convert to Christianity, most Muslims are converts from Christianity, I mean, who would that much?

528
01:10:41,000 --> 01:10:52,000
And he said, the worst thing he said was, you can tell by looking at John, we won't have anybody else who does that, people laughed.

529
01:10:52,000 --> 01:11:10,000
But that was, we maintained a friendship, I didn't talk to him that much afterwards, but, and that's why to this day, I mean, I have warm, fuzzy memories of, of Minister Jeremiah Shabbat,

530
01:11:10,000 --> 01:11:24,000
he was just a good guy, he was just a good guy caught in a situation where he was, because he was good-hearted, I think he was pushed around by the nation.

531
01:11:24,000 --> 01:11:35,000
They like cold-blooded people who could get it done, and that's why they got rid of Malcolm. He's trying to protect, hey, look, he was too sincere, too honest, too real,

532
01:11:35,000 --> 01:11:45,000
to, it's like people who go into an organization, look at the mission statement, say, wow, that's a wonderful mission, and they go do it.

533
01:11:45,000 --> 01:11:55,000
And the people in the organization say, well, we don't really want to do that, we just say we want to do that, you're going to cause problems if you really do that, so that's where that went.

534
01:11:55,000 --> 01:12:01,000
Maybe, maybe, maybe, more to say about your reaction to his killing in 665?

535
01:12:01,000 --> 01:12:05,000
Oh, oh, my goodness, I was devastated.

536
01:12:05,000 --> 01:12:09,000
I was devastated.

537
01:12:09,000 --> 01:12:21,000
One of the things I learned from Malcolm, and one of the sad things about what people were expecting from leaders in those days, people came to you,

538
01:12:21,000 --> 01:12:26,000
and if you were supposed to be a leader, you were supposed to have answers.

539
01:12:26,000 --> 01:12:42,000
So nobody comes to you and say, how can I help? They come with criticisms of what you're trying to say, okay, you know, I'm the time kind of guy, if I see you're trying to do something, I'm going to say, alright, this is what you need.

540
01:12:42,000 --> 01:12:46,000
Okay, we need to talk about policy.

541
01:12:46,000 --> 01:12:53,000
If you're going to do this particular thing, then we need to talk about policy, or you need to talk about whatever it is that's going on.

542
01:12:53,000 --> 01:12:59,000
And okay, I can handle this segment here. I'll do this for you, Malcolm, I'll do this. I can handle this.

543
01:12:59,000 --> 01:13:05,000
And then you're expecting other people in the room to say, well, I'll handle this. They're all like, what's you going to do, Malcolm?

544
01:13:05,000 --> 01:13:11,000
What's you going to do? Nobody's taking any responsibility.

545
01:13:11,000 --> 01:13:28,000
So I was pretty devastated at his death, and you know, again, put his picture in the window window, and, and, you know, it's just one of those things.

546
01:13:28,000 --> 01:13:40,000
But one of the things I learned is that, and what upset me the most was the people who said, I remember being a black Muslim and talking to people about the nation when I was all going, ho.

547
01:13:40,000 --> 01:13:47,000
And their thing was, yeah, we love Malcolm. If he wasn't with the nation of Islam, we would follow him.

548
01:13:47,000 --> 01:14:01,000
So I took note of those people, and when he left the nation of Islam, I said, okay, he's out now. He's got this community organization that we're trying to organize, and dealing with issues that affect people's lives.

549
01:14:01,000 --> 01:14:11,000
You know, this isn't rhetoric anymore. It's about now trying to, you know, he's at his epiphany, and he's, he's seeing that, you know, it's not going to be based on race.

550
01:14:11,000 --> 01:14:16,000
He's, he's, he's trying to, you know, still help the, the people who need the most help.

551
01:14:16,000 --> 01:14:26,000
Oh, well, you know, and so the same people who wouldn't take a risk then wouldn't take a risk afterwards. And so I learned a lot about human nature.

552
01:14:26,000 --> 01:14:39,000
And I'm clear that people who aren't willing to be afraid with you are, are no help to you at all, because whenever you're trying to make a change, I don't care what the issue is.

553
01:14:39,000 --> 01:14:49,000
There's always this scary part where, yes, you could fail. Whatever the object is, you could fail, you could be made a laughing stock.

554
01:14:49,000 --> 01:15:02,000
But if you feel it's the right thing, even though you are afraid, there's something about taking that step in spite of how you feel, you do it.

555
01:15:02,000 --> 01:15:11,000
And there is vindication in it, the winner lose. I've been in fights that I've lost, and I don't mean physical fights, because I lost all of them.

556
01:15:11,000 --> 01:15:18,000
But I mean, you know, struggles, community struggles that have really not worked out well.

557
01:15:18,000 --> 01:15:29,000
But what has made me feel good is I was in it to win it. I took a principle, what I believed to be a principal position.

558
01:15:29,000 --> 01:15:40,000
I went on record with that position. And if I lost, or we didn't get what we wanted, I can still sleep well at night because I was on the right, from my point of view.

559
01:15:40,000 --> 01:15:51,000
I was on the right side of the issue. And the way history works is eventually it comes back around, and people decide to do the right thing at some point later on.

560
01:15:51,000 --> 01:15:58,000
And when they go back and check the history, they said, oh yeah, well, he was for this 10 years ago when it wasn't popular.

561
01:15:58,000 --> 01:16:04,000
So I don't make a big deal when it goes, oh, I just say, yeah, well, that really vindicates my position.

562
01:16:04,000 --> 01:16:11,000
So let me ask one more thing, and then we'll take a break. Maybe I'll bring him relax from there to come back and talk more about all the work you've done for the healthy.

563
01:16:11,000 --> 01:16:19,000
But one more thing, 63, 64, say, through SNCC, through the nation coming up to Philadelphia.

564
01:16:19,000 --> 01:16:25,000
Did you, at that point, you mentioned in meeting some of the folks who were purported to be not represented.

565
01:16:25,000 --> 01:16:29,000
So you had a sense that maybe these guys were not who they said they were.

566
01:16:29,000 --> 01:16:41,000
And finally in that broad context, did you have an active sense even then that you might have become yourself a person kind of who, you know, FBI and all of those guys were watching?

567
01:16:41,000 --> 01:16:46,000
Oh my god, they came to me. It was not very subtle then.

568
01:16:46,000 --> 01:16:54,000
No, in fact, I've never asked for, I've never made a request for my file, which I guess I should do at some point.

569
01:16:54,000 --> 01:17:01,000
But the FBI came to my, when I started the Freedom Library, I'm sitting there and there come to me about James Forman.

570
01:17:01,000 --> 01:17:11,000
You know they're just moved to get white churches to give money for reparate, whatever it was at the time.

571
01:17:11,000 --> 01:17:20,000
And I just said, you see that I'm here trying to start a school for kids.

572
01:17:20,000 --> 01:17:31,000
I haven't broken any laws. And if you think that I'm going to give you information to deal with James Forman, first of all, I don't have any such information.

573
01:17:31,000 --> 01:17:47,000
And secondly, you know, you guys can't, you know, when we called you, when people were being lynched and you said you couldn't do anything, but you have time now to try to pin something on a guy who hasn't broken any laws yet.

574
01:17:47,000 --> 01:17:52,000
But you want to build a case? What is this? So they huffed out.

575
01:17:52,000 --> 01:18:01,000
And I knew at that point the fact that they came, and there was another thing to let me know, when I came back to Philly, I was trying to get a job somewhere.

576
01:18:01,000 --> 01:18:16,000
And the guy said, you're on the pink list. You're on the pink list because they had me as both a Muslim and a communist and radical, some kind of stuff they had.

577
01:18:16,000 --> 01:18:30,000
And I, you know, so yeah, I have known. And another thing too, I went back to visit. I forgot what year it was. I went down south to visit either in 66 or 67.

578
01:18:30,000 --> 01:18:41,000
And I don't even remember when. And people told me that the FBI had been in touch with them and said that I was coming and probably coming to FOMET violence. I mean, it was just that.

579
01:18:41,000 --> 01:18:54,000
And I think, again, you know, I'm my, I cannot be accurate about my years. I mean, I tried to be as accurate as I could be in that. But some of these events, I can't tell you really what year it was.

580
01:18:54,000 --> 01:19:06,000
But I know it was after I had been back in Philly and decided to go back to visit and folk from there said the FBI told them watch out. He's coming. He's, you know, it was just ludicrous.

581
01:19:06,000 --> 01:19:26,000
It was just, and it tickles me because I've never had a gun, never owned a gun, never advocated that anybody have a gun. I was not, I never advocated non violence in the sense that John Lewis did and does.

582
01:19:26,000 --> 01:19:36,000
But I never advocated violence. It was, it was the kind of thing I always would think about what would I do if somebody attacked my mother?

583
01:19:36,000 --> 01:19:48,000
Forget me. What would I do if somebody attacked my mother and I'm in the room? I'm going to sit there and pray for them. You better not think that. Or my kids. What am I going to do if somebody comes in here to attack my kids?

584
01:19:48,000 --> 01:20:02,000
So rather than take a position, pro violence, anti-violence, I said nothing on issue. Rather, I talked about creative violence versus destructive violence. But anyway, that's.

585
01:20:02,000 --> 01:20:21,000
I'll tell you I can go far. We're back on after short break. I wanted to pick up with with your vision and the perspective and goals that you add in your freedom, freedom life.

586
01:20:21,000 --> 01:20:31,000
Okay, I wanted to do a couple of things. One is my experience in SNCC and with the Black Muslim movement in Atlanta particularly.

587
01:20:31,000 --> 01:20:48,000
Made me see that Black history was something that not only energized me, but energized people that I met who had no sense of their history, who were just thinking they were stuck in a rut.

588
01:20:48,000 --> 01:20:58,000
And I saw people change their behavior. I saw people begin to have hope for the future and to begin the plan for that hope.

589
01:20:58,000 --> 01:21:13,000
And so I thought that a library of books buying about Black people right on Rejavano and a heart of North Philadelphia, two blocks away from projects, high-rise projects.

590
01:21:13,000 --> 01:21:37,000
Next door to a bar would be the perfect place to begin to have people feel better about themselves. And so I looked at it from purely a, it was a faulty analysis, but nonetheless it was an analysis that the problem with Black people was we didn't know our history.

591
01:21:37,000 --> 01:21:52,000
And if we knew our history we'd be better off. Of course that is the most fallacious proposition one can have, but hey, I was young, I was still what, 2021 I forgot, I was in my early 20s.

592
01:21:52,000 --> 01:22:14,000
Okay, so that was my rationale and the school type thing, when we started, before I talk about the school, when we started we were just collecting books, buying about Black people and beginning to put them up in the library.

593
01:22:14,000 --> 01:22:24,000
And then we had Wednesday night history classes and we'd have a delts and Wednesday nights were fun because we would get people from the bar next door.

594
01:22:24,000 --> 01:22:39,000
And what was wonderful is I began to look at people differently, all my life, people who hung out in my mind, people who hung out in the bars were drunkards, whatever.

595
01:22:39,000 --> 01:22:54,000
And this is of course before, I believe it was before cheers was on the air. So I learned before cheers came on that people really like bars because everybody knows their name.

596
01:22:54,000 --> 01:23:05,000
And so when we had our Black history lectures, people from the bar would come over and would share their knowledge.

597
01:23:05,000 --> 01:23:18,000
I mean, you can't tell based on who knows what. And so sometimes I would have done my homework and my research and I'd begin to hold forth.

598
01:23:18,000 --> 01:23:30,000
And God from the bar next door said, no, no, no, no, that didn't happen until 1875. This is what happened, bang, and he starts talking.

599
01:23:30,000 --> 01:23:44,000
And then the other people would chime in, oh yes, well that was, have you read such and such John? No, I haven't. Well, I won't bring it to you next week before you talk to us again about this, you need to read.

600
01:23:44,000 --> 01:23:57,000
And so it was a wonderful, it was both humbling and exciting because it helped me early on to realize you're not here to solve a problem.

601
01:23:57,000 --> 01:24:04,000
You're here to learn and elicit from people what they know and empower them to do what they need to do.

602
01:24:04,000 --> 01:24:17,000
And so your job is to provide an opportunity and take that same opportunity yourself to learn, to learn where people's heads are, to appreciate them, to encourage them.

603
01:24:17,000 --> 01:24:25,000
And so I learned so much from those early sessions, which were really booked as I'm going to teach you Black history. That's how I started.

604
01:24:25,000 --> 01:24:39,000
And it got to be, let's talk about Black history and let's hope I can learn some along the way. And it was just wonderful. Then, then there was a situation where there were some kids who needed some tutoring.

605
01:24:39,000 --> 01:24:50,000
So we started, I wasn't doing any tutoring, I just let, you know, people wanted to do it. And there's one day there were a bunch of kids in there and the tutor didn't show up.

606
01:24:50,000 --> 01:25:06,000
And I got stuck, I couldn't let them go home, I started tutoring and then the next day the person didn't show and then I was tutoring. And then in tutoring the kids I'm discovering, I'm trying to help them with work that they don't understand.

607
01:25:06,000 --> 01:25:18,000
And they can't understand it because three steps back, they didn't get that. So if I'm going to help them as a tutor, I've got to go back those three steps and build them up to where they are.

608
01:25:18,000 --> 01:25:38,000
And forget about what their homework is and go back and give them the fundamentals that they need so that they can catch up. And I started doing it. And of course that sort of lent itself to, I'm doing this with kids who are in school and not having a great deal of success because it's hard.

609
01:25:38,000 --> 01:25:51,000
It's hard to be in sixth grade with a third grade or fourth grade understanding and not getting it and trying to bring you up to snuff in a short period of time.

610
01:25:51,000 --> 01:26:01,000
So the idea came, let me start with some preschool kids who haven't been to school yet, haven't been corrupted by the terrible, egregious education system.

611
01:26:01,000 --> 01:26:20,000
And so I didn't know anything about teaching preschoolers. So there was a teacher that I knew and I asked her to come through and teach. She said fine. And she was using the look-safe method and she was working with the kids. And I'm watching them sitting there and then what all of a sudden she can't do it anymore.

612
01:26:20,000 --> 01:26:36,000
She's like, I can't do this anymore. I got to work. I can't do this. So I started with the look-safe method and I said there's a way, how did I learn to read?

613
01:26:36,000 --> 01:26:52,000
And I remember that standing up at the blackboard with Mrs. Freed in first grade talking about going through the phonetics of the alphabet and then putting an A in front of it and an E.

614
01:26:52,000 --> 01:27:21,000
I went, how that came back to my memory, I don't know. I started working with the kids on phonetics and then I discovered the Lippincott book series. There was, in those days, books put out by Lippincott which would have, which if you use their system, had kids reading two years above whatever anybody else was reading.

615
01:27:21,000 --> 01:27:35,000
It was just wonderful. I bought the series, started with, and I started working with kids and getting excited about the fact that kids could start with phonics and you could move them into reading.

616
01:27:35,000 --> 01:27:53,000
My kids were my own kids, my own kids were guinea pigs for this and they were reading, gee with, my youngest son David was reading at about a year and a half.

617
01:27:53,000 --> 01:28:11,000
My other kids were also, and what I loved about the Lippincott books was that they would hit you with new stuff all the time and they teach you how to deal with the AU. What does that sound?

618
01:28:11,000 --> 01:28:33,000
It was just, it's like I found a miracle. And so then we started talking about, okay, let me set this up. So we started teaching four days a week, two hours a day. And what I did in starting the school was just go in the neighborhood, like the Pied Piper.

619
01:28:33,000 --> 01:28:51,000
And I would go to people that I had worked with on trying to get them to do rent strikes and history who lived in neighborhoods and said, hey I want your kids. You got little kids between two and a half, you know, long as they don't pee on themselves I got them. I can work with them. No diapers, you know, two and a half to five I'll take it.

620
01:28:51,000 --> 01:29:16,000
So I just started teaching those kids every day, four days a week and just for two hours and focusing on reading and focusing on math. And after I did that for about two years I just, you know, incorporated, you know, got a little, got my friend was a lawyer to incorporate Freedom Library, day school ink.

621
01:29:16,000 --> 01:29:42,000
And I started having kids come and I remember when the school opened I had 10, 15, 20 kids that I would do for free. And when I said, okay, it's now $10 a week. And I knew that $10 a week even then was cheaper than any babysitter. And for $10 a week I'll feed your kids lunch. It's five days a week. I'll feed them lunch.

622
01:29:42,000 --> 01:30:06,000
And I know all you got to do is bring them and pick them up and I'll take care of them for the whole week. And I had three students. And I worked on those students. I remember distinctly sitting in the Freedom Library praying, God, if you will give me 10 students. I might be able to make a living at this.

623
01:30:06,000 --> 01:30:32,000
And he never gave me 10. It was 3, 3, 3, and then it was 14. Then it moved to something like 20 something. And when it got up to, I think I was teaching up to 35 or 40 kids in a single classroom. And then I grabbed my mother who always wanted to teach. And she took the older kids, I took the younger kids.

624
01:30:32,000 --> 01:31:01,000
One of the wonderful experiences that I had in teaching the kids is I would use what's called the individual prescriptive method of teaching. So without knowing what that was, I would, if I was working with George over here and George could read faster and understand what was going on, then the seven or eight kids in his group, I let George go.

625
01:31:01,000 --> 01:31:27,000
And give him work to make sure that he, you know, check him out, listen to him. And then I'd work on the other kids. And it ended up that most of the kids were operating on their own sort of like it was hard for me to group them because there were some kids who were who, let's say that George was up to page 45 and begging for more.

626
01:31:27,000 --> 01:31:48,000
And this guy next to him was on page 14, but plotting along. Somebody might be on page 25. And so what I would do is just kind of spend time with each person and encourage the kids. And it got to be where I finally I had so many kids, I had to group them, but I allowed them to push each other.

627
01:31:48,000 --> 01:32:00,000
So I would have George read if he read very well. And the other kids would want to read as well as George read, I'm making up George. I don't think I ever had a George, but that's okay.

628
01:32:01,000 --> 01:32:15,000
But the fun thing in all of this was I learned about teaching, which was counter to everything that I had ever heard about teacher education.

629
01:32:16,000 --> 01:32:25,000
I mean, the teachers that I met were telling me that my methods were just horrendous. They were not working. My kids were reading. They were doing new math.

630
01:32:26,000 --> 01:32:44,000
They understood what a set was and they knew what a subset was. And so it was, it was really, I was experimenting, but I was, I was energized. And at the same time, I hated it.

631
01:32:45,000 --> 01:33:01,000
I didn't, I never, this is what is weird. I enjoyed the interaction with the kids seeing them learn, but I hated teaching because it was hard work. I'm up at night. After the kids are gone, they all have written homework that I give them.

632
01:33:01,000 --> 01:33:20,000
And I've got to go through 45 books and give each person separate. I can't give one sheet and say do that because everybody's at a different level. The kids who were doing math were at different levels. Somebody had just started long division. Somebody was still on addition or subtraction.

633
01:33:20,000 --> 01:33:46,000
And I had to look and just progressively stay with each kid and make sure that they were being built up in a systematic way. So that meant I had to sit there with these homework books. And get them ready for the next day because when they came to school the next day and I'd give them the corrected whatever they did the night before I had to give them the next book.

634
01:33:46,000 --> 01:34:11,000
I didn't care if you were two and a half years old, you had homework and it was writing, if you know making your A within the lines down, down, across, whatever it was. So it was, it was both exciting and exhilarating and it was, if you ask me then, I enjoy it in retro spec because I'm thinking about it.

635
01:34:11,000 --> 01:34:23,000
But I remember distinctly hating it, but I had to do it. I couldn't quit and I did it for 14 years and then quit. I was burned out at the end.

636
01:34:23,000 --> 01:34:27,000
Did it feel like a radical project to do that?

637
01:34:27,000 --> 01:34:44,000
No, it was, it was, it was what was necessary. It was what they needed. I wanted to, I wanted to give them not only during this period, I ran into other nationalists who had schools.

638
01:34:44,000 --> 01:35:01,000
And their emphasis was on, in my view, on rhetoric. And so they had all of the black stuff and they had the drums and they had this. I had none of those things. My thing was, you got to have skills and you got to know about your blackness.

639
01:35:01,000 --> 01:35:13,000
So it was history, it was, you know, you need to be strong in character and I always push those character traits, you know, honesty, integrity, you know, hard work, you know, all the stuff.

640
01:35:13,000 --> 01:35:18,000
And smart work, not necessarily hard work, but smart work.

641
01:35:18,000 --> 01:35:43,000
So those were the things that I pushed. And in dealing with other educators who were working with kids and I had, I had real issues with Amari Baraka, who, and his mentor, out in California.

642
01:35:43,000 --> 01:35:56,000
Why am I forgetting his name because I've read him and did some doctoral work related to some of his ideas.

643
01:35:56,000 --> 01:36:15,000
Well, I could, Karanga, Ron Karanga. I was very concerned that, that kids be, that skill sets be built as well as an ideological base.

644
01:36:15,000 --> 01:36:27,000
And I just thought that they spent too much time on an ideological base without giving the kids the skills. And so the kid can tell you by root whatever it is that he tells you.

645
01:36:27,000 --> 01:36:37,000
I'd rather the kid tell you by root his timetables and stuff that he can use when he's navigating in the world.

646
01:36:37,000 --> 01:36:50,000
And I got together with some other people and we formed the, the CB, the Council of Independent Black Institutions.

647
01:36:50,000 --> 01:37:05,000
And that was in the 70s. I can't tell you exactly when at 70, maybe 71, 72. For two years, I set up a teacher training institute and just using stuff that I did, got them to come to Philly at the Freedom Library Day School.

648
01:37:05,000 --> 01:37:15,000
And from 6am to 11am in night, we had a two week training course for teachers who were in independent black school.

649
01:37:15,000 --> 01:37:25,000
And they had to learn how to, how to teach and stuff that they had to do was how to make a black board.

650
01:37:25,000 --> 01:37:38,000
So that you know, you can start from scratch. You don't have any money to be equipped like a regular school would be, but you know, how do you get the black board paint and how do you, you know, answer we would make the black boards.

651
01:37:38,000 --> 01:37:48,000
We would, and we use the church around the corner and you make room dividers, you know, physically make room dividers.

652
01:37:48,000 --> 01:37:55,000
You would have to go out in the neighborhood and recruit kids and we do it in the summertime.

653
01:37:55,000 --> 01:38:04,000
You go out in the neighborhood, you recruit, you talk to parents, you recruit the kids, you tell them we're doing this Freedom School is going to be for one week.

654
01:38:04,000 --> 01:38:10,000
I think we did the school for one week, but they had a one week training before that and then they had training while they were doing the one week.

655
01:38:10,000 --> 01:38:21,000
And the object in the end was so that when they walked away they had a real sense of what does it take to start a school, what do you need to do, how do you work with the kids, how do you work with the problems that they present to you.

656
01:38:21,000 --> 01:38:37,000
There was very little theoretical, I mean, there was some theory. I tried to give them an overview of what they could expect, but you know, and that the things that you are to expect, you've got to figure, you've got a week to overcome.

657
01:38:37,000 --> 01:38:48,000
You've got a week to overcome a situation with a child who comes in, who everybody says is learning disabled and you cannot treat him or her as if they're learning disabled.

658
01:38:48,000 --> 01:38:57,000
You have to treat that child as if and you must demand from that child the same thing you demand from the kid next to him who is not learning disabled.

659
01:38:57,000 --> 01:39:04,000
And what I've discovered, what I did discover in those days is, and I had a number of children who came to my school like that.

660
01:39:04,000 --> 01:39:16,000
Every one of those children who came like that left, I'm not going to tell you they were A students, but they were C students. They could hang in anybody's elementary school and do C work.

661
01:39:16,000 --> 01:39:21,000
And as long as they could see their way through, they'd be fine.

662
01:39:21,000 --> 01:39:25,000
So lots of things came out in that.

663
01:39:25,000 --> 01:39:31,000
It's really good to have you talk about that because I can see the investment and all the work that you did across those years.

664
01:39:31,000 --> 01:39:36,000
Let me pull you back to 64, 65, 66.

665
01:39:36,000 --> 01:39:45,000
Because while you're starting the school work, the library is also becoming, as I understand, and I need you to tell me if this is correct or not.

666
01:39:45,000 --> 01:39:53,000
So I don't think of a real kind of locust for lots of folks with lots of interesting ideas we're thinking hard about strategies for moving forward.

667
01:39:53,000 --> 01:40:08,000
I know that people across the spectrum of black nationalism, separatism, and it will, some of that effort will build towards in February 66 the creation of black people's units.

668
01:40:08,000 --> 01:40:10,000
Oh yes, yes, got all about that.

669
01:40:10,000 --> 01:40:18,000
And so I'd love to have you talk a little bit about how the momentum gathered to lead to the creation of black people's unit movement, I think Julian Bond is your keynote or perhaps, that's right.

670
01:40:18,000 --> 01:40:20,000
That's right, that's right, that's right.

671
01:40:20,000 --> 01:40:24,000
Just have you tell that story.

672
01:40:24,000 --> 01:40:27,000
Okay.

673
01:40:27,000 --> 01:40:32,000
And part of, and this is good.

674
01:40:32,000 --> 01:40:53,000
During this period when we're doing that, we've been working with gangs, we've been working with, in our work with gangs, I got to know Father Paul Washington of the Church of the Advocate who has a history of his own here in Philadelphia.

675
01:40:53,000 --> 01:41:08,000
He's deceased at this point, but he was, he was the guy in North Philly as a priest who let us have room to voice our nationalism.

676
01:41:08,000 --> 01:41:18,000
And that was unique because most churches, I mean, there was anybody else who was about to have us even meet, we were tainted, I mean, just to, and he was, he was open.

677
01:41:18,000 --> 01:41:30,000
He had his own views, but he, he really worked hard at, at being open and seeing, you know, positive progress.

678
01:41:30,000 --> 01:41:38,000
So in my work with the gangs, there was, there was a friend of his who offered to give me a salary to do that.

679
01:41:38,000 --> 01:41:44,000
So I'm like, you know, I got kids, I got a wife, I, I, I needed it.

680
01:41:44,000 --> 01:41:52,000
So I took the funny, it was a little bit, but I could, I could, hey man, you give me 25 bucks, I can do a lot of it.

681
01:41:52,000 --> 01:42:02,000
So there was, that happened. And as I was working with the gangs, the, the donor wanted one thing.

682
01:42:02,000 --> 01:42:13,000
And as I was working with the gangs, I'm seeing something else. I'm seeing, I can develop these guys into real leaders who can do some positive things in their community.

683
01:42:13,000 --> 01:42:30,000
They can, you know, the violence thing is just a piece of it. I remember having a conversation with one gang member and I'm, I'm passionately trying to tell him about, help me get this, this treaty with this other gang.

684
01:42:30,000 --> 01:42:38,000
He looked at me, he said, John, gang warring is my life.

685
01:42:38,000 --> 01:42:47,000
That's all I have. That's what I live for. You take away gang warring from me. I have nothing.

686
01:42:47,000 --> 01:42:56,000
And I couldn't answer him. I couldn't tell him, well, if you prepare yourself, you know, you could do this. He was giving me his gut.

687
01:42:56,000 --> 01:43:07,000
And I was silent. I couldn't answer him. And so that made me go back to the drawing table and say, okay, what lies beyond peace?

688
01:43:07,000 --> 01:43:15,000
If I don't want him to gang, well, what do I have to offer this guy that can be part of his life that makes sense to him?

689
01:43:15,000 --> 01:43:26,000
And so my first thing is, okay, we need people who will protect people in the community. You can use your skills.

690
01:43:26,000 --> 01:43:33,000
We need old ladies protected and not molested or bothered or robbed.

691
01:43:33,000 --> 01:43:41,000
And they got interested in that. I mean, it was a role. It was like, we need our own police. It was getting to that level.

692
01:43:41,000 --> 01:43:48,000
Yeah, getting to that level. And it's like, you know, and I remember this guy bought into it.

693
01:43:48,000 --> 01:43:55,000
It was, well, when the guy who was funding the program saw that, he said, oh, no, this is not, this is not what I'm paying you to do.

694
01:43:55,000 --> 01:44:02,000
And I said, wait a minute. You paid me because I was doing work with the gangs that I thought was necessary.

695
01:44:02,000 --> 01:44:09,000
I'm not going to do what you want me to do that is not in the best interest of these kids I'm working with.

696
01:44:09,000 --> 01:44:19,000
And so he cut the money and he sent Paul Washington to tell me in a nice way, you know, either shape up or, and I told Paul,

697
01:44:19,000 --> 01:44:26,000
I mean, that's when I had a confrontation with Paul about, man, you better figure out what sides you're on.

698
01:44:26,000 --> 01:44:39,000
You can't be a go-between. You have to take sides. You're either with a community or you're with your church and with the people who are oppressing this community.

699
01:44:39,000 --> 01:44:47,000
You got to make up your mind where you are. And I knew by having a conversation that that could mean I can't use this church anymore.

700
01:44:47,000 --> 01:45:00,000
And I just, it was, this is what we had. And he thought about it. He controlled himself. I knew he wanted to say, man, I, do you know what I've done for you?

701
01:45:00,000 --> 01:45:10,000
But he didn't go there. He listened to me. He was thoughtful. And he just said, okay, well, you know that I'm not in charge of the money.

702
01:45:10,000 --> 01:45:19,000
You know, you know, you've just blown, I said, fine, I've done that, but I still need a place to meet. And he said, okay, fine, you can still use the advocate.

703
01:45:19,000 --> 01:45:39,000
And so I just kept doing what I was doing. And in that process, we talked about a black unity movement. And what we wanted to do was we wanted a movement that could include gang members, that could include old ladies, young people,

704
01:45:39,000 --> 01:46:01,000
professionals, people who were aspiring for politics. We wanted to have people who were musicians or dancers. The thing that made the B-Pum, the black people's unity movement different from every other movement that I've known about, is that we tried to make it inclusive.

705
01:46:01,000 --> 01:46:18,000
So we had Arthur Hall, who was a famous African dance, he had a famous African dance troupe. We had John, the guy who started Freedom Theatre here in Philadelphia, John Allen.

706
01:46:18,000 --> 01:46:40,000
We had his group, so we had artists, we had musicians, we had people who were aspiring for political, one of the guys who actually who ended up running for political office and becoming a state senator, state rep in this area, Richardson.

707
01:46:40,000 --> 01:47:07,000
David P. Richardson was one of the young guys at the time who was part of this. And we had lawyers, we had doctors, we really had. And we tried to get people to see, what is it that, how can we look at each other and not alienate each other, be alien from one another.

708
01:47:07,000 --> 01:47:17,000
We had that represent the interest of the group we represent here. So if I'm a doctor, don't tell me to sing, come by, yeah, that's not what I hear before.

709
01:47:17,000 --> 01:47:24,000
How much room was in there for ideological diversity across? How much?

710
01:47:24,000 --> 01:47:39,000
Oh, there was lots of, because what I was interested in at that point was getting people together. And one of the things that I learned about getting people together is, you get, I mean, you get seven people in a room, you're going to have 14 points of view.

711
01:47:39,000 --> 01:47:56,000
So if you're not ready to tolerate 14 points of view, and what I was always interested in is, what's the bottom line? What can we find that we all agree on? We never tried to take a position as the black people's unity movement that was so radical that people who were in it couldn't buy it.

712
01:47:56,000 --> 01:48:10,000
So what we were really pushing was just, how do we work together, what kinds of programs or things that we can come up with that we can all say, hey, that's a good idea.

713
01:48:10,000 --> 01:48:23,000
And if there are real estate people who say, hey, we need to educate black folks about buying property. Well, nobody's going to argue with that. Let's do that. Let's have a seminar on that.

714
01:48:23,000 --> 01:48:49,000
Yeah, let me ask about that year of 66, which has a whole lot of very, a lot happens in 66 around this effort. But to set the stage for that, I have read that the black people's unity movement was organized around two founding principles. And they have to be really illustrate the strength of feeling and perspective about the nature of the US culture and society at the time.

715
01:48:49,000 --> 01:49:08,000
And what one possible happening forward would be for black Americans. One principle was that white supremacy and racial inequality were constitutive of US culture that they were part of the culture of the nation very forward.

716
01:49:08,000 --> 01:49:23,000
And that had to be acknowledged and confide and related to that was the fact that there are progress wrapped in the Americans, dependent on large part on intracuracial resources that goes of earlier conversations about some Lewis.

717
01:49:23,000 --> 01:49:52,000
And just as the movement really starts to move forward, February of 66, it's not money. Many ones later before there's a massive police raid in coming right after that movement and its close affiliates. And some very interested in having you talk a little bit about how you felt you were reaching forward and then that raid and its implications.

718
01:49:52,000 --> 01:50:09,000
Well, you're talking about the infamous SNCC Dynamite case. It's very interesting. One of the things that had happened while we were doing the school was there was a guy who came who was called Casamiro Parirra.

719
01:50:09,000 --> 01:50:23,000
We discovered from one of our informants that he was a police plant. We didn't know this before. He came and he wanted to set up a thing where he would have martial arts for the young people.

720
01:50:23,000 --> 01:50:41,000
Well, I wasn't opposed to that. It's okay. But then he started talking about, well, I've got some M16s that I want to bring to the school. Oh no, my man. No, we don't need rifles. We don't even need fake rifles. Much less real rifles.

721
01:50:41,000 --> 01:50:56,000
And I kind of watched him and other people who were around kind of watched him. Somebody saw him sitting up in the police having conversations and they got it back to me.

722
01:50:56,000 --> 01:51:13,000
And I never said anything to him that I knew that he was a police informant. But there were always attempts during that period. People would float in and try to instigate some kind of stupid something to try to get you hung up.

723
01:51:13,000 --> 01:51:30,000
And it was lots of situations where people would buy it. In fact, I believe, and I don't know this for a fact, but I believe that the guy who got arrested on the dynamite case somebody posing as a construction worker went to him and said, look, I got this dynamite.

724
01:51:30,000 --> 01:51:51,000
I said, oh my God, you can't have that. Well, would you hold it for me? I don't know what to do. And then that's when it, and then they stuck it on him. The raid was this guy talked to me. And I'm telling him, man, don't have nothing to do with nobody's dynamite.

725
01:51:51,000 --> 01:52:04,000
You leave it where you found it. Let the police know that it's there. It's probably a setup to put you in trouble. Oh, man, I can't call the cops, man, because the guy is out of it.

726
01:52:04,000 --> 01:52:17,000
And I think in that case, the guy was a police informant who said him, but anyway, in the meantime, the police used that. Rizzo was the police chief at the time before he got to be mayor.

727
01:52:17,000 --> 01:52:34,000
And he came to the Freedom Library in 66, yeah, about February. Yeah, because my wife at the time was very pregnant. And they just about one o'clock in the morning broke down the door.

728
01:52:34,000 --> 01:53:03,000
Absolutely, right upstead. And they just broke down into a came up the steps, bulletproof vests and the sort off shot guns. And I happen to be up. I don't know why I was up at one o'clock in the morning. My God, it would have been a mess if I had been asleep and awakened by this. And up in our face. And I was concerned about my wife and my wife was just horrified by it. And she was angry. And she started.

729
01:53:03,000 --> 01:53:24,000
You know, fussing and I'm like, look guys, we'll talk about this in a minute. If you got a search, will you search the bedrooms where I can put my wife there? And I'm thinking, I don't want to die tonight because if she says something and you guys hit her, I can't live with her if I don't do something.

730
01:53:24,000 --> 01:53:48,000
You know what I mean? It's just one of those things. And so I just kept talking quietly and calmly. And I guess I was in shock. You know, when you're in shock, you don't really feel you just trying to solve a problem. And that's where my mind was. It's like, okay, let me cooperate with you. You need to search. I didn't even ask them what they were searching for.

731
01:53:48,000 --> 01:53:59,000
I just said, would you search the bedroom first? Let me put my wife in there and close the door. Then you can do whatever you need to do. So finally, they let that happen.

732
01:53:59,000 --> 01:54:12,000
As soon as that was calm, here comes the captain up the steps. And he thoughts all over again. And he's pushing me around trying to get me to do something stupid. Just, well not really stupid. They just want me to say something.

733
01:54:12,000 --> 01:54:29,000
And they'll call it resisting arrest. And I'm like, you know, what is it that you have to do? Just do what you need to do. I'm not resisting anything. I'm here. I don't even know what this is about. And I didn't fuss. I didn't complain. I didn't say anything.

734
01:54:29,000 --> 01:54:46,000
And they thought, I'm tearing, I'm sealing down and I found out later they were looking for dynamite. So eventually they left. They couldn't get a rise out of me.

735
01:54:46,000 --> 01:54:59,000
Now, I'm going to tell you, I didn't feel the terror until they walked down. I couldn't sleep for nights on end because every sound that came into the street, I'm like this.

736
01:54:59,000 --> 01:55:09,000
I called my lawyer and I saved my lawyer because he was a friend and he was in the Black People's Unity movement, William Lee Acres.

737
01:55:09,000 --> 01:55:27,000
And last I heard he was a federal magistrate in California. But William Lee Acres, I've always trusted him. He was just a straight shooter, good lawyer, tough guy.

738
01:55:27,000 --> 01:55:37,000
And he, I called him up and told him about everything and he said, John, they had a warrant. There's nothing we can do.

739
01:55:37,000 --> 01:55:53,000
And when he told me that, I just said, okay, that was a big moment for me because I was enraged, I was traumatized. And my feelings were hurt.

740
01:55:53,000 --> 01:56:09,000
And he was like, how have I behaved in this neighborhood? I've never had a gun. I've never talked in all of my militant speeches. You'll never hear me talk about rise up and kill the crackers.

741
01:56:09,000 --> 01:56:24,000
But that wasn't my rhetoric. It was never on that level. So I mean, so a lot of feelings going on. And I flip back to the night of the thing.

742
01:56:24,000 --> 01:56:39,000
And when the cops left, there was a big group of people outside who were ready to confront the cops. And I calmly, even though I was upset, said, look, we're going to handle this in a legal way. Please go home. They want you to do something.

743
01:56:39,000 --> 01:56:50,000
They're prepared for you to do something so that they can, you know, mow you down, basically. And so they disperse and went home.

744
01:56:50,000 --> 01:57:05,000
And when my lawyer told me there was nothing I could do, I had to make a decision. And the decision I made was, I'm not going to let my hurt feelings. I'm not going to let my pride and all the things that, you know, I was, I was violated.

745
01:57:05,000 --> 01:57:23,000
I can't let that mess with me because there is nothing that I can do. I mean, I can make noise. I can fuss about it. But it's wasted energy. And I will be getting off track from what I need to be doing to help people.

746
01:57:23,000 --> 01:57:34,000
This is something that happened to you, John. And, you know, you can't get it confused with what you're trying to do for people. And so I sucked it up, basically.

747
01:57:34,000 --> 01:57:43,000
And I was wise to do so.

748
01:57:43,000 --> 01:57:58,000
I want to say this. So it's in the record that that rate. It was August 13, 1966. FBI and police in the city of Philadelphia, the SNCC office, the Freedom Library to the Department.

749
01:57:58,000 --> 01:58:13,000
It was an 80-armed, you know, a riot-year clad of law enforcement officers in the thousand youth from Biden. And I mean, this was really a massive show of law enforcement authority by the white police establishment.

750
01:58:13,000 --> 01:58:35,000
I mean, I'm just going to say, is there a connection between, well, let me ask you sort of to take us forward from that summer of 1966 towards, you know, it's the spring when James Tade is re-elected. No, sorry.

751
01:58:35,000 --> 01:58:53,000
So we re-elected in the fall of 1967. And the spring of 1967, it makes sure it is a police commitment. So that happens. And then in the summer of 1967, that's when David Richardson asks the PUM to help organize high school students. And I don't know if you had a lot of direct engagement of that issue.

752
01:58:53,000 --> 01:58:58,000
No, I didn't. No, I didn't. But you know the story about what happened to those kids.

753
01:58:58,000 --> 01:59:02,000
And then it comes to a certain echo and culmination. Sure.

754
01:59:02,000 --> 01:59:16,000
So maybe you could tell that story. No, I can't because I wasn't really, I tend to, I have learned for good or ill to function with blinders.

755
01:59:16,000 --> 01:59:33,000
And it's like I determined where my territory is. And there are lots of things that happen. There are a lot of issues that come up. And I have disciplined myself to stay focused on, on, on stay in my lane and just focus.

756
01:59:33,000 --> 01:59:43,000
I heard about what was happening with the kids. It was just a, it was like a massacre that went on. But I did not get involved in it. There were some kids who came to the library and talked about it.

757
01:59:43,000 --> 01:59:55,000
And I kind of dealt with those individual kids and, and, you know, talked to them. But I did not try to get into that.

758
01:59:55,000 --> 02:00:06,000
One of the things that that goes back to my mother is always asking me to examine my motives. I always questioned why I would take an action.

759
02:00:06,000 --> 02:00:31,000
So I was never running to get in the paper or running to be quoted. There were times when I was quoted or, you know, but those were things that I did not run toward because I couldn't trust my motives if I were doing that. And it would be like my attitude about certain movement people who sort of looked like they were running around to get press.

760
02:00:31,000 --> 02:00:44,000
I would not go name any names, but particularly right after Dr. Martin Luther King died, there was a certain gentleman who seemed to be in the limelight all the time and had a different story about history than the other people who were there.

761
02:00:45,000 --> 02:00:57,000
But anyway, I always questioned. And so I wouldn't get involved in something even though I might care about it or it might affect me if it was not in the scope of work that I had set out to do.

762
02:00:57,000 --> 02:01:08,000
And if I, if I couldn't answer the question of what's your motive, are you, are you doing that because it's hot now? And I couldn't, I couldn't do that.

763
02:01:08,000 --> 02:01:14,000
How do you, how do you push forward after 66, 67?

764
02:01:14,000 --> 02:01:39,000
I continued doing what I was doing basically. I continued school till 1978. I was the head of B.Pum for a while and then we had a moment. I think in 66 is when I had this Jesus encounter.

765
02:01:39,000 --> 02:01:53,000
And so there was a meeting of B.Pum, which I just kind of shared with everybody that, hey, this is where I am and as long as I'm chairman, we're going to use Jesus' leadership principle.

766
02:01:53,000 --> 02:02:17,000
And somebody in the audience said, well, how do we get rid of you? I said, it's as simple as voting me out and they did. And I felt very good about that. I mean, I took that Paul in approach. I had, you know, was across the Christ. I had been evicted. I was quite pleased with myself.

767
02:02:17,000 --> 02:02:34,000
And so there was a period right after that when it appeared that I lost all credibility. People were calling me, you know, he's crazy, he's a Jesus freak, what happened to John? He's not radical anymore.

768
02:02:34,000 --> 02:03:00,000
And it is precisely that that was the beginning of my real, I think, radical development because I saw Jesus as a revolutionary and I saw him and still see him as one who calls me to account for everything and requires that I make whatever bold moves I need to make for the benefit of folk.

769
02:03:00,000 --> 02:03:29,000
And in fact, and to have the strength to do it by myself, if need be. And if other people come along, know how to treat them and enjoy them, but to stay the course. So that it was an interesting period because after that, that's when people who had been friends kind of dropped off. And I changed the history nights to Bible study nights and people were like, ah, this man has lost his mind.

770
02:03:30,000 --> 02:03:55,000
And that just happened for a while. And as life would have it, I just continued being who I was. And over time, I'm still dealing with issues, still dealing with community concerns. And I'm not doing it in even in a religious being, people expected that at that point, oh, he'll probably start preaching. No way.

771
02:03:55,000 --> 02:04:21,000
I wasn't even going to church. It was a while. That I started going to church and found that very frustrating. So it was a kind of commitment. I'll say that where I have some similarity to John Lewis. I mean, I just stayed the course.

772
02:04:21,000 --> 02:04:38,000
I mean, people were opposed. And I just, hey, this is, this is what I have to do. I'm not angry with you because you can't do it or you don't want to do it. I'm not trying. I'm not an evangelist. I'm not trying to get you saved. I'm just doing what I got to.

773
02:04:38,000 --> 02:04:56,000
Did you participate in the effort that was underway like 60s or early 70s to contest? Try to reorganize democratic party politics to collect more after the Americans in the city or that?

774
02:04:56,000 --> 02:05:16,000
No, I didn't. I had a real bad. I was very anti politics. And and and reason I was is because I had a fresh sense from from snake. I want to see people empowered to do. And what happened? It happened in the poverty.

775
02:05:16,000 --> 02:05:41,000
I'll call it. People came up who called themselves community leaders who might have been. And they got caught in the money. It was all about let's get the funding to do. Everybody was on my funding. And it just drove me to well, I'm going to do this stuff without funding. I'm not asking anybody for money. I'm going to do what I got to do.

776
02:05:41,000 --> 02:05:48,000
And it was amazing that we could get stuff done without funding and other people who were being funded were just being funded.

777
02:05:48,000 --> 02:05:57,000
I think you can come right here and you're leading to the whole war on poverty and other cities funding streams that began to come out of Johnson and the streets.

778
02:05:57,000 --> 02:06:07,000
People people and I just if it was a valid something you know that had to deal with do with connecting directly with people.

779
02:06:07,000 --> 02:06:17,000
Hey, I don't care who you were if you were doing something valid with people. I could support that. I could you know do whatever I could training or whatever you wanted me to do.

780
02:06:17,000 --> 02:06:25,000
But I wasn't going to have to any of the money and I wasn't going to support this camp against that camp. I just had no.

781
02:06:25,000 --> 02:06:33,000
As we say in the black community, y'all got that. Nothing to do with that at all.

782
02:06:33,000 --> 02:06:41,000
Resident will become there at 71. What's your difference in the like the 68s? So at the federal level you kind of see here and build up the.

783
02:06:41,000 --> 02:06:49,000
And Resident's on my thing, the candidate who made some of the same arguments and on the stomach. Very useful for it.

784
02:06:49,000 --> 02:06:59,000
And how do you feel about the community and build up the and not build up the movement forward into the 70s?

785
02:06:59,000 --> 02:07:09,000
Well, in 70s from I was very active. What I would do when things got frustrating for me at the local level, I would do national stuff.

786
02:07:09,000 --> 02:07:28,000
And so the the the CB, the Council of Independent Black Institutions, I got very involved in developing the curriculum and planning for those two years of the trainings and and you know meeting with people and talking about that.

787
02:07:28,000 --> 02:07:43,000
And around and at the same time the the the CBS documentary had been done in 68.

788
02:07:43,000 --> 02:07:54,000
And I think they aired it in 69. So I had some follow up from that people would I got a chance to speak in different colleges.

789
02:07:54,000 --> 02:08:06,000
I had a chance to do work with kids in Chicago. We're actually did some demonstration things which were fun. I mean just meeting kids I didn't know and trying to do it.

790
02:08:06,000 --> 02:08:14,000
And would tell them you know if you don't let anybody come and tell you how to teach kids who isn't teaching kids and why and letting you watch.

791
02:08:14,000 --> 02:08:28,000
I don't know any of these kids. I don't even want to talk to you if you don't have kids for me to work with. And then you can critique me or whatever you want to do but but but you shouldn't listen to anybody who's talking about teaching kids who doesn't teach kids.

792
02:08:28,000 --> 02:08:38,000
So I had a good time in Chicago. I was trying to be mean to the kids. They just laughed at me. They didn't take me seriously. I mean they they knew where I was coming from.

793
02:08:38,000 --> 02:08:59,000
This was post-built. Yeah. So during that period it's sort of like I had a focus outside of Schilling. I mean I could go here I could go there I could work on these these larger projects that would have I thought national impact.

794
02:08:59,000 --> 02:09:15,000
And so those were the things that I was interested in. And I and that was a strong period of the struggle between what I would call revolutionary nationalism and the and cultural nationalism.

795
02:09:15,000 --> 02:09:30,000
And the people out of California and in Newark we're talking about cultural nationalism. So people were supposed to wear certain garb and be African and do this. And I'm talking about revolutionary nationalism.

796
02:09:30,000 --> 02:09:42,000
And what we need to do is to develop politically but we need to develop not within the system the corrupt political system because we can see that it's based on something that isn't cool.

797
02:09:42,000 --> 02:09:55,000
We've got to we've got to test people we've got to train people we've got to have people who whom the community trusts. And then we've got to get the community then to elect them to office outside of the machine.

798
02:09:55,000 --> 02:10:09,000
Well you know that's that doesn't happen in some of the best communities in this country. You just can't beat the machine. And it's not just Chicago. It's filling its New York. Atlanta is wherever you are.

799
02:10:09,000 --> 02:10:36,000
Very very. And it still is. It still is. It still is. So during that period the national work was what kept me and I've I've tend to have that that view that whenever I run in if I'm working on a project and I run into a snare or a stump.

800
02:10:36,000 --> 02:10:49,000
There's a place where I can't go anywhere. I let it sit for a minute and go do something else. And by the time I get finished doing this something else I come back to the other project and I can go with it.

801
02:10:49,000 --> 02:11:04,000
So I that's one of the ways that I keep myself from being discouraged. You know there's always something to do and it's just a matter of focusing on that one thing or two things and doing it when you get into something that you can't go any further.

802
02:11:04,000 --> 02:11:17,000
You go back to the first thing and you can move that forward. So that's pretty much what I did in those years.

803
02:11:17,000 --> 02:11:29,000
Dr. Churchill thank you for such generous contribution. I want to spend some time as you would like as much as you would like to be talking about.

804
02:11:29,000 --> 02:11:38,000
You have been really forged a clear remarkable commitment to community and have been involved in so many efforts to carry the community forward.

805
02:11:38,000 --> 02:11:44,000
And I'd love to hear about some of the things that have been occupying most of your energies and efforts for some time now.

806
02:11:44,000 --> 02:11:49,000
Okay. Thanks for the opportunity.

807
02:11:49,000 --> 02:12:05,000
Right now or when I say right now between 2006 and now there's been a I've been very interested in well maybe I should start before that.

808
02:12:05,000 --> 02:12:15,000
And there was a period in my life and in about 1995 I was in a serious car accident.

809
02:12:15,000 --> 02:12:22,000
And it I was supposed to die but I didn't.

810
02:12:22,000 --> 02:12:31,000
And it really by this time I was practicing law, you know I had a law degree, I was practicing law.

811
02:12:31,000 --> 02:12:41,000
And it really helped me kind of refocus again on what was really mattered in life, what are the points.

812
02:12:41,000 --> 02:12:51,000
And after that experience I got interested in taking theology to another level.

813
02:12:51,000 --> 02:12:56,000
So it was not a change in my commitment.

814
02:12:56,000 --> 02:13:08,000
But it was okay I think it's time for you John to kind of do some study of theology, kind of go to seminary, kind of kind of get that together.

815
02:13:08,000 --> 02:13:16,000
Not necessarily to be a preacher but just for your own philosophical theological development.

816
02:13:16,000 --> 02:13:22,000
And so that experience did more than anything to help me realize that the practice of law was not fun.

817
02:13:22,000 --> 02:13:29,000
I was not having fun. And in the practice of law I was I did some very interesting thing.

818
02:13:29,000 --> 02:13:34,000
One I started out as a farm worker attorney for these.

819
02:13:34,000 --> 02:13:40,000
So there you go. Start out as a farm worker attorney in New Jersey.

820
02:13:40,000 --> 02:13:51,000
And that reminded me of being in Mississippi and in Georgia because in the the the the early 90s South Jersey

821
02:13:51,000 --> 02:14:10,000
Cumberland County and Salem County were to be out at night and to be a lawyer representing the farm workers was like asking for somebody to shoot you.

822
02:14:10,000 --> 02:14:19,000
So after a year of this I couldn't take it.

823
02:14:19,000 --> 02:14:22,000
Just the fear family just honestly the fear factor.

824
02:14:22,000 --> 02:14:25,000
Let me come to Philadelphia and practice law and fill it.

825
02:14:25,000 --> 02:14:33,000
Let me start a practice that deals with the elderly and you know a state planning which was really what I wanted to do.

826
02:14:33,000 --> 02:14:40,000
So when I came here to do that then I got involved in criminal law which I had in plan to do.

827
02:14:40,000 --> 02:14:43,000
And so I'm working with a lot of young people who are being charged.

828
02:14:43,000 --> 02:14:52,000
And I'm getting interested in the kids. I'm taking their cases. I'm fussing with them. I'm trying to get them to come to the office.

829
02:14:52,000 --> 02:15:02,000
I'm trying to figure out how I can you know when I get you past this case I need you know I need you to come and work with me.

830
02:15:02,000 --> 02:15:14,000
I need you to you know and it becomes very frustrating. So by the time I had this accident in 95 it was like you know what I need to do something different.

831
02:15:14,000 --> 02:15:17,000
I really need to move in another direction. I didn't know what to do.

832
02:15:17,000 --> 02:15:25,000
And so the accident sort of slowed me down enough that I at least had a chance to think about it.

833
02:15:25,000 --> 02:15:35,000
So I began to develop what's called the Church for Leadership Institute. I started talking about leadership training and I got involved in okay.

834
02:15:35,000 --> 02:15:47,000
Let me take these biblical principles that Jesus taught and that Moses taught and that the prophets taught and all the good guys, the wisdom books.

835
02:15:47,000 --> 02:15:54,000
How do I translate this stuff so it isn't religious but it's just practical sound advice that people can use.

836
02:15:54,000 --> 02:16:01,000
I don't even have to call it what it is. I can just say you know teach it from that. So I started getting interested in that.

837
02:16:01,000 --> 02:16:17,000
Still wanted to do this whole thing about black education in terms of you know kids and what's happening in our schools and you know just try to figure out how to work that in.

838
02:16:17,000 --> 02:16:37,000
And so I was on this sort of development and by the time the so I went to Lutheran Theological Seminary and while I was there I got disturbed by fellow students.

839
02:16:37,000 --> 02:16:59,000
I'm not trying to get looked at by a bishop. Some they are and I just didn't have much patience with folks who could not see their role as leaders of a community and that it was that the bishop.

840
02:16:59,000 --> 02:17:18,000
I'm not saying be be bad to your bishop. I'm just saying that there ought to be a calling that is people centered and that allows you to have a commitment to the people in your congregation and to serve as a leader of that congregation to help people do the kinds of things they need to do in their communities.

841
02:17:18,000 --> 02:17:47,000
So while I was there I had an opportunity to think more deeply about getting heavier in theology and of course I had a couple of good professors but I wanted to do something you know after I had my courses and my basic reading that I had done on my own and find a raise these issues in class you can raise them but students didn't want to discuss it because it's like that's you know I just wanted to do that.

842
02:17:47,000 --> 02:18:16,000
I just want to get my piece of paper and get out of here. This is a graduate level thing. So I went to union, not union, since in that I did school in Union Institute and University and started a study in black and African African.

843
02:18:17,000 --> 02:18:36,000
I took on American studies. At the same time I took online courses at why am I blanking at another university.

844
02:18:36,000 --> 02:19:04,000
We have your CV in the records. So I was doing the theological courses and the black history stuff and I began to develop wanted to talk about and think about an issue that was interesting to me which was the relationship of religious thought

845
02:19:04,000 --> 02:19:33,000
to whether people are quiet or active whether they're self-liberative. And so I did my thesis on that which was quite interesting. You could find cases on both sides where there were folks who used as we did in SNCC I would say who used the gospel to empower them to fight.

846
02:19:33,000 --> 02:19:49,000
And there were other cases and terrible cases and particularly in mining towns where that was used to keep the miners from really revolting and keep them down.

847
02:19:49,000 --> 02:20:13,000
So that kind of thing I ended up I had a chance to teach at Lutheran Theological Seminary for a year. It was a very discouraging process. They didn't like me and I didn't like them. But it was a good experience and I learned from other colleagues who were teaching in other places when they told the truth.

848
02:20:13,000 --> 02:20:41,000
Nobody really wants to learn. It's a mill and people are coming in and they're going out and they're just trying to get their piece of paper and so don't be frustrated. But I was frustrated because I'm one of those people who I'm not quite a purist but it's like if you're in a theological institution it seems to me that you really ought to be committed to knowing as much as you can know having as many tools in your hand as well.

849
02:20:41,000 --> 02:20:56,000
Because you can't solve a problem anyway. None of us by ourselves can solve any problem. We can have the greatest ideas in the world but we need each other to put in our best thought to the thing to do it. And if you're not going to give it any effort my God and you're a leader what is happening.

850
02:20:56,000 --> 02:21:24,000
Anyway to move forward in 2006 actually in 2005 I started a little church called Liberation Fellowship Church of Jesus and it was a non-religious church in the sense that yes there is word. I have a sermon every Sunday and it is taken from the Bible but it is related to practical leadership lessons.

851
02:21:24,000 --> 02:21:48,000
I always talk about it in terms of leadership lessons. So we've had in our first services we had Muslims, we had atheists, we had all kinds of folks who would just come because it was kind of different in front of us. We had it right here in this place where people just, you know, it's not just a sermon. After the sermon we have a question and answer period people are able to express themselves.

852
02:21:48,000 --> 02:22:02,000
And then we have Bible study and the Bible study is not this is this, you know, it's not like this is what you want to get out of this. It is what do you see? What is the say to you? How does it speak to you? What do you get from it? How does that relate to your life?

853
02:22:04,000 --> 02:22:14,000
And it seems like people were kind of energized by that and could look at things a little deeper than the regular religious labels.

854
02:22:14,000 --> 02:22:32,000
And out of that the early congregation said, hey, why don't we put together a community development corporation and we're here in Germantown, why don't we do that? So the whole, all of us, all five of us, or six, I think our biggest number was seven.

855
02:22:32,000 --> 02:22:55,000
And we all pitched in and everybody had to write a piece of it. Everybody had to, it was a collective document at the end so that everybody got the experience of putting together a CDC and finding out, of course, I help people with this, it has to be this, it has to be that, but you're going to help put it in.

856
02:22:55,000 --> 02:23:23,000
And so we filed and we got our 501C3 thing and people felt really good. I mean, hey, they were involved in the process. And so the next thing was, what are we going to do with this thing? And we started, I remember, in fact, I was just talking to Nancy about this, was it yesterday, sweetheart? One day, just talking about, gee, I remember one new year's Eve talking about with my wife, what are we going to do?

857
02:23:23,000 --> 02:23:42,000
We've got this 501C3 thing and we said we were going to do these things. And we just had this long conversation and we started the next day, New Year's Day, planning how to really get that done.

858
02:23:42,000 --> 02:23:57,000
And so what we've been doing since then is we have a, we have a, an HIV AIDS program, and I call it a program, but it's community education.

859
02:23:57,000 --> 02:24:17,000
And so, in the education, Nancy and I both went to take our little courses to be certified as testers. And so, and as counselors, HIV AIDS counselors. So we, factors back in June, we had a, we had a health fair in the, in Vernon Park, a couple of blocks from here.

860
02:24:17,000 --> 02:24:31,000
We tested people and we had folks come through and, you know, we had some testing for ear hearing, we had, we had a dental truck out there, we had people testing for hepatitis, we, you know, just kind of.

861
02:24:31,000 --> 02:24:38,000
So that's one of the thrusts that we, we do that. Another thing is we started the Greater Germantown Business Association.

862
02:24:38,000 --> 02:24:57,000
And I'm the, I keep calling myself the interim president. There's a guy who says, you just get rid of the interim church bill, you know that you're the president. My theory is that one day, we will really happy elections and, you know, folk from the community will take hold.

863
02:24:57,000 --> 02:25:22,000
But as it is now, it's, I'm, you know, I'm just doing, but we have a good group of people, we have, the history of that, there used to be a Germantown Business Association years ago. And it deteriorated because there were, most of the people were real estate people who were trying to control property.

864
02:25:22,000 --> 02:25:45,000
So they would have arguments at meetings and any little guys coming in would get caught in the crossfire. They just banned it. And when we were talking about community development here, economic, sustainable economic development in Germantown, it's like, wait a minute, we can't, as a CDC, talk about that unless there is a partner who, you know, we've got to have the business community involved in this.

865
02:25:45,000 --> 02:26:14,000
So we looked around to see who was around and there's nothing, nothing was going on. And so we started the Greater Germantown Business Association. And my wife and I went door to store to store and to try to get people interested. And when we went out there, people looked at us like we were nuts as, it's not different than in the 60s when you first go out, people look at you like you're a nut and you just keep going back, you keep going back, you've given them a lot of money.

866
02:26:15,000 --> 02:26:42,000
So we said, this is the literature, we need to do, we're having our first meeting here. These are the things we're going to be talking about. And so at our first meeting, we had like 43 businesses show up. We said, oh, this is great. And we talked about people signing up and, you know, paying their annual dues. And at the next meeting, we had with three people, four people. But since we started, we have never not had our monthly meeting except for July or August.

867
02:26:42,000 --> 02:27:07,000
So the association is growing. We've got some good strong businesses in it. One of the things that we're concerned about is having in Germantown and inclusive, diverse business association that reflects all the cultures. We've got, we've got Arabs, we've got Muslims, we've got Africans, we've got Asians, we've got specifically, we've got a good Korean business community.

868
02:27:07,000 --> 02:27:36,000
They don't live in the area, but they're here. And our job is to try to make everybody feel at home because this is a, this is a very diverse neighborhood. So that's our goal with that. So we've been, we've been pushing that and it's been growing. In fact, now one of our biggest projects, the things that I'm most excited about now, is that the Liberation Fellowship Community Development Corporation has turned out to be a great place for us.

869
02:27:36,000 --> 02:28:05,000
The Liberation Fellowship Community Development Corporation has taken on the task of redeveloping a place called Town Hall. It's here in Germantown at 59, 28 Germantown Avenue. It is, it is the oldest town hall in the state. Quakers found Quakers and Minonites, founded Germantown. Yeah, there were Quakers and Minonites who founded Germantown and I'm going to get the year wrong, but it's 16, I think it's 1681.

870
02:28:05,000 --> 02:28:29,000
It's one of those. Within seven years of its founding, the birthplace of the anti-slave movement was right here in Germantown before filling with the city. And then it got incorporated into Philadelphia. It had a town hall. So that building has been here, not that same building, but on that spot there was a town hall from the 17th century.

871
02:28:29,000 --> 02:28:47,000
And what happened is that the city, it was a civil war hospital. I mean, it still was a town hall, but the only battle we had in Germantown, it was that there was the hospital down the hall, taking care of people on both sides of the aisle.

872
02:28:47,000 --> 02:29:12,000
And so it has a lot of history and it has been lying in disrepair since 1994-95. And we have developed a project to acquire the building and when we first mentioned this in 2008 or 2009, it's when we came up with the idea.

873
02:29:12,000 --> 02:29:24,000
And our councilwoman laughed us to score. You got $35 million.

874
02:29:24,000 --> 02:29:38,000
And I just felt impelled. My wife went along with me, but she was like, I think you've been smoking something when I wasn't looking job.

875
02:29:38,000 --> 02:29:51,000
But I mean, I had this vision. It had to happen. And so there was this whole low now in 2011. When I go to people with the idea, we've got a team of people, we've got architects on the team.

876
02:29:51,000 --> 02:30:06,000
I just had a meeting last week with the mayor's office of sustainability here in Philly. She wants more information, but there is not a year crazy. It is a hey. Have you thought about this? Yes, we've thought about that. Have you thought about that?

877
02:30:06,000 --> 02:30:17,000
Oh, no, we didn't. That's a good idea. And she's going to put us in touch with some other people. So it is. That's where I am now. And let me tell you what it's for.

878
02:30:17,000 --> 02:30:35,000
We want to develop the building as a state of the art building using geothermal and solar. It's going to be a green building. It will also be a place for a dual education level.

879
02:30:35,000 --> 02:30:54,000
One will be STEM subjects, science, technology, engineering, and mathematics. And that is for in my brain, I see a rival to MIT right here in Germantown in this neighborhood.

880
02:30:54,000 --> 02:31:16,000
At the same time and in the same place, I want to see green college job training, training in just plumbing, heating, electricity, welding, all the kinds of green things that allow people to earn income at a living wage.

881
02:31:16,000 --> 02:31:39,000
And one of the things that is critical is right across the street from Germantown High School, which is one of the poorest performing high school. And the current district attorney has suggested that town hall should be developed as a criminal justice center, which is basically a court or a place to house people.

882
02:31:39,000 --> 02:31:54,000
The next argument is it ought to be a place when the kids look across the street that they can say, when I leave here, if I'm not going to college and I could take college courses over there, I could at least get some basic skills so that I can be employable.

883
02:31:54,000 --> 02:32:08,000
The two things, and the third thing we want to do in that building is to have a green business incubator. So we want this to be state of the art and that's the other thing, the other avenues that we're involved in.

884
02:32:08,000 --> 02:32:25,000
So that's the project, but it incorporates our interest in environmental education. And so we have that as part of what we do. When the 2011 Brownfields Conference came to Philadelphia, we were one of its sponsors here.

885
02:32:25,000 --> 02:32:35,000
And so that just gives you an idea of some of the things that we're interested in. And so my life is still full, very busy.

886
02:32:35,000 --> 02:32:41,000
So, I'm so afraid from this issue that you have never been someone to sit around and watch the world go by.

887
02:32:41,000 --> 02:32:50,000
No. So, it's going to be a real R and a preparation. Very, very grateful. Thank you on behalf of the museum and the library. This is going to be a great privilege to be with you.

888
02:32:50,000 --> 02:32:53,000
All right, and thank you. It's been fun.

889
02:32:53,000 --> 02:33:06,000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

